# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ritual
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] Alfred Reginald Radcliffe-Brown was born Alfred Reginald Brown in Sparkbrook, Birmingham, England, the second son of Alfred Brown (d.1886), a manufacturer's clerk, and Hannah Brown (née Radcliffe).
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] He later changed his surname, by deed poll, to Radcliffe-Brown, Radcliffe being his mother's maiden name.
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] He was educated at King Edward's School, Birmingham, and Trinity College, Cambridge (B.A., 1905; M.A., 1909), graduating with first-class honours in the moral sciences tripos.
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] At Trinity College, he was elected Anthony Wilkin student in 1906 and 1909.
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] While still a student, he earned the nickname "Anarchy Brown" for his close interest in the writings of the anarcho-communist and scientist Peter Kropotkin.
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] Rivers who, with Alfred Cort Haddon, guided him toward social anthropology.
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] With the latter's influence, he travelled to the Andaman Islands (1906–1908) and Western Australia (1910–1912, with biologist and writer E.
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] Grant Watson and Australian writer Daisy Bates) to perform fieldwork concerning the workings of the societies there.
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] His time in the Andaman Islands and Western Australia were the basis of his later books *The Andaman Islanders* (1922) and *The Social Organization of Australian Tribes* (1930).
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] At the 1914 meeting of the British Association for the Advancement of Science, in Melbourne, Bates accused him of plagiarising her work, based on an unpublished manuscript she had sent him for comment.
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] Before departing for Western Australia, Brown married Winifred Marie Lyon in Cambridge; they had one daughter, Mary Cynthia Lyon Radcliffe.
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] The couple became estranged by about 1926.
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] They may have divorced in 1938 (sources disagree on whether a divorce was completed).
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] In 1916 Brown became a director of education in Tonga.
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] In 1921 he relocated to Cape Town to become professor of social anthropology, initiating the School of African Life.
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] Further university appointments were University of Cape Town (1921–1925), University of Sydney (1925–1931) and University of Chicago (1931–1937).
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] Among his most prominent students during his years at the University of Chicago were Sol Tax and Fred Eggan.
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] While at the University of Sydney, he was a cultivator of the arts, and championed Edward de Vere, 17th Earl of Oxford as the author of the works attributed to Shakespeare.
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] Fearing that the Depression would result in financial collapse, Radcliffe-Brown departed in 1931 for a professorship with the University of Chicago, leaving his successors to solicit Rockefeller grants and government funds to save the Sydney Department.
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] After these various far-flung appointments, he returned to England in 1937 to begin an appointment to the first chair in social anthropology at Oxford University in 1937.
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] He had this post until his retirement in 1946.
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] Survived by his daughter, he died in London in 1955 at the age of 74.
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] While Radcliffe-Brown founded the Institute of Social and Cultural Anthropology at Oxford, according to Rodney Needham his absence from the institute during the war years prevented his theories and method from having a major influence on Oxford anthropology.
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] Radcliffe-Brown was influenced by his tutor, W.
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] Rouse Ball, to study a moral science (psychology, philosophical subjects, and economics) instead of a natural science which he originally wanted to choose.
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] During his time at Cambridge, professors Haddon and Rivers encouraged him to study anthropology and discover his interests in the topic.
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] Haddon guided him towards the comparative method in specific societies in anthropology, classification and morphology, inductive generalization, and to sympathize with Durkheim's methods.
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] He has been described as "the classic to Bronisław Malinowski's romantic".
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] Radcliffe-Brown brought French sociology (namely Émile Durkheim) to British anthropology, constructing a rigorous battery of concepts to frame ethnography.
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] Durkheim inspired Radcliffe-Brown throughout the entirety of his profession in anthropology.
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] One of Radcliffe-Brown's goals was to "transform anthropology into a 'real' science based on the natural sciences".
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] He demonstrated these ideologies in his book published in 1957, *A Natural Science of Society*.
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] In 1906, one of Alfred's primary studies concerned the kinship and familial relations of Western Australians.
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] Within these communities, he discerned distinct social organizations that proved that adaptation and fusion were essential in keeping the system functioning.
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] The term "Structural Functionalism" would later be used to describe the idea that "the life of a society may be viewed as an active system of functionally consistent, interdependent elements".
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] Radcliffe-Brown has often been associated with functionalism, and is considered by some to be the founder of structural functionalism.
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] Structural Functionalism, which can be traced back to sociologist Émile Durkheim, is the social theory that assumes societal institution (e.g.
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] Government, school systems, family structures, etc.) play a role in its success.
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] Alfred developed these principles believing that studying social structures like kinship ties would be evidence enough for understanding how social structures affect the maintenance of a society, stating, "human beings are connected by a complex network of social relations.
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] I use the term "social structure" to denote this network of actually existing relations".
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] (On Social Structure, 190) He also clarifies that "We may define it as a condition in which all parts of the system work together with a sufficient degree of harmony or internal consistency, i.e., without producing persistent conflicts which can neither be resolved nor regulated".
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] (On the Concept of Function in Social Science, 181).
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] Nonetheless, Radcliffe-Brown vehemently denied being a functionalist, and carefully distinguished his concept of function from that of Malinowski, who openly advocated functionalism.
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] While Malinowski's functionalism claimed that social practices could be explained directly by their ability to satisfy basic biological needs, Radcliffe-Brown rejected this as baseless.
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] Instead, influenced by the process philosophy of Alfred North Whitehead, he claimed that the fundamental units of anthropology were processes of human life and interaction.
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] Because these are by definition characterized by constant flux, what needs explaining is the occurrence of stability.
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] Why Radcliffe-Brown asked, would some patterns of social practices repeat themselves and even seem to become fixed?
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] He reasoned that this would at least require that other practices must not conflict with them too much; and that in some cases, it may be that practices grow to reinforce each other, a notion he termed 'coadaptation', deriving from the biological term.
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] Functional analysis, then, was just the attempt to explain stability by discovering how practices fit together to sustain that stability; the 'function' of practice was just its role in sustaining the overall social structure, insofar as there was a stable social structure (Radcliffe-Brown 1957).
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] In addition to identifying abstract relationships between social structures, Radcliffe-Brown argued for the importance of the notion of a 'total social structure', which is the sum total of social relations in a given social unit of analysis during a given period.
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] The identification of 'functions' of social practices was supposed to be relative to this total social structure.
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] Lévi-Strauss considered social structure as a model.
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] Radcliffe-Brown's research emphasized simple, non-literate societies.
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] He believed kinship played a large role in these societies, and that patrilineages, clans, tribes and units all relate to kinship rules in society and are essential in political organization.
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] Radcliffe-Brown claimed that all research on social structure is based on observations, what anthropologists see and hear about individual peoples.
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] Radcliffe-Brown also argued that the study of social structure encompassed culture, therefore there is no need for a separate topic dedicated to culture.
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] A major opinion concerning tribal societies had been that all societies follow a unilineal cultural sequence ('evolutionism'), and that therefore 'primitive' societies could be understood as earlier stages of that sequence; conversely, 'modern' societies contained vestiges of older forms.
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] Another opinion was that social practices tend to develop only once, and that therefore commonalities and differences between societies could be explained by a historical reconstruction of the interaction between societies ('diffusionism').
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] According to both of these opinions, the proper way to explain differences between tribal societies and modern ones was historical reconstruction.
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] Radcliffe-Brown rejected both of these opinions because of the untestable nature of historical reconstructions.
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] Instead, he argued for the use of the comparative method to find regularities in human societies and thereby build a genuinely scientific knowledge of social life.
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] To that end, Radcliffe-Brown argued for a 'natural science of society'.
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] He claimed that there was an independent role for social anthropology in that respect, separate from psychology, though not in conflict with it.
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] This was because psychology was to be the study of individual mental processes, while social anthropology was to study processes of interaction between people (social relations).
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] Thus he argued for a principled ontological distinction between psychology and social anthropology, in the same way as one might try to make a principled distinction between physics and biology.
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] Moreover, he claimed that existing social scientific disciplines, with the possible exception of linguistics, were arbitrary; once our knowledge of society is sufficient, he argued, we will be able to form subdisciplines of anthropology concerning relatively isolated parts of the social structure.
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] But without extensive scientific knowledge, it is impossible to know where the boundaries should be defined.
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] Radcliffe-Brown was often criticised for failing to consider the effect of historical changes in the societies he studied, in particular changes brought about by colonialism.
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] Nevertheless, he is now considered, along with Bronisław Malinowski, as one of the founders of modern social anthropology.
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] Radcliffe-Brown performed extensive fieldwork in the Andaman Islands, Australia, and elsewhere.
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] On the basis of this research, he contributed extensively to the anthropological ideas concerning kinship, and criticised Lévi-Strauss's Alliance theory.
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] He also produced structural analyses of myths, including on the basis of the concept of binary distinctions and dialectical opposition, an idea later echoed by Lévi-Strauss.
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] According to Radcliffe-Brown, the function of religion is to install a sense of dependence on fear and other emotional strain on the human body into a society.
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] Therefore, a major function of religion is to affirm and strengthen sentiments necessary for a society to continue.
[src:ritual/a-r-radcliffe-brown] This idea was developed in Radcliffe-Browns book, *The Andaman Islanders* (Free Press 1963).
[src:ritual/aarne-thompson-uther-index] The **Aarne–Thompson–Uther Index** (**ATU Index**) is a catalogue of folktale types used in folklore studies.
[src:ritual/aarne-thompson-uther-index] The ATU index is an essential tool for folklorists, used along with the Thompson (1932) *Motif-Index of Folk-Literature*.
[src:ritual/aarne-thompson-uther-index] Austrian consul Johann Georg von Hahn devised a preliminary analysis of some 40 tale "formulae" as introduction to his book of Greek and Albanian folktales, published in 1864.
[src:ritual/aarne-thompson-uther-index] Reverend Sabine Baring-Gould, in 1866, translated von Hahn's list and extended it to 52 tale types, which he called *"story radicals"*.
[src:ritual/aarne-thompson-uther-index] Jacobs expanded the list to 70 tale types and published it as "Appendix C" in Burne & Gomme's *Handbook of Folk-Lore*.
[src:ritual/aarne-thompson-uther-index] Before the edition of Antti Aarne's first folktale classification, Astrid Lunding translated Svend Grundtvig's system of folktale classification.
[src:ritual/aarne-thompson-uther-index] This catalogue consisted of 134 types, mostly based on Danish folktale compilations in comparison to international collections available at the time by other folklorists, such as the Brothers Grimm's and Emmanuel Cosquin's.
[src:ritual/aarne-thompson-uther-index] Antti Aarne was a student of Julius Krohn and his son Kaarle Krohn.
[src:ritual/aarne-thompson-uther-index] Aarne developed the historic-geographic method of comparative folkloristics, and developed the initial version of what became the Aarne–Thompson tale type index for classifying folktales, first published in 1910 as *Verzeichnis der Märchentypen* ("List of Fairy Tale Types").
[src:ritual/aarne-thompson-uther-index] The system was based on identifying motifs and the repeated narrative ideas that can be seen as the building-blocks of traditional narrative; its scope was European.
[src:ritual/aarne-thompson-uther-index] The American folklorist Stith Thompson revised Aarne's classification system in 1928, enlarging its scope, while also translating it from German into English.
[src:ritual/aarne-thompson-uther-index] In doing so, he created the "AT number system" (also referred to as "AaTh system") which remained in use through the second half of the century.
[src:ritual/aarne-thompson-uther-index] Another edition with further revisions by Thompson followed in 1961.
[src:ritual/aarne-thompson-uther-index] The AT-number system was updated and expanded in 2004 with the publication of *The Types of International Folktales: A Classification and Bibliography* by German folklorist H.-J.
[src:ritual/aarne-thompson-uther-index] Uther noted that many of the earlier descriptions were cursory and often imprecise, that many "irregular types" are in fact old and widespread, and that "emphasis on oral tradition" often obscured "older, written versions of the tale types".
[src:ritual/aarne-thompson-uther-index] To remedy these shortcomings Uther developed the Aarne–Thompson–Uther (ATU) classification system and included more tales from eastern and southern Europe as well as "smaller narrative forms" in this expanded listing.
[src:ritual/aarne-thompson-uther-index] He also put the emphasis of the collection more explicitly on international folktales, removing examples whose attestation was limited to one ethnic group.
[src:ritual/aarne-thompson-uther-index] The Aarne–Thompson Tale Type Index divides tales into sections with an AT number for each entry.
[src:ritual/aarne-thompson-uther-index] The names given are typical, but usage varies; the same tale type number may be referred to by its central motif or by one of the variant folktales of that type, which can also vary, especially when used in different countries and cultures.
[src:ritual/aarne-thompson-uther-index] The name does not have to be strictly literal for every folktale.
[src:ritual/aarne-thompson-uther-index] For example, *The Cat as Helper* (545B) also includes tales where a fox helps the hero.
[src:ritual/aarne-thompson-uther-index] Closely related folktales are often grouped within a type.
[src:ritual/aarne-thompson-uther-index] For example, tale types 400–424 all feature brides or wives as the primary protagonist, for instance *The Quest for a Lost Bride* (400) or the *Animal Bride* (402).
[src:ritual/aarne-thompson-uther-index] The entry concludes, like others in the catalogue, with a long list of references to secondary literature on the tale, and variants of it.
[src:ritual/aarne-thompson-uther-index] In his 1997 essay "The motif-index and the tale type index: A critique", American folklorist Alan Dundes explains that the Aarne–Thompson indexes are some of the "most valuable tools in the professional folklorist's arsenal of aids for analysis".
[src:ritual/aarne-thompson-uther-index] They have, however, been subject to criticism concerning their construction, where they apply, and what they exclude.
[src:ritual/aarne-thompson-uther-index] The tale type index was criticized by V.
[src:ritual/aarne-thompson-uther-index] Propp of the Russian Formalist school of the 1920s for ignoring the *functions* of the motifs by which they are classified.
[src:ritual/aarne-thompson-uther-index] Furthermore, Propp contended that using a "macro-level" analysis means that the stories that share motifs might not be classified together, while stories with wide divergences may be grouped under one tale type because the index must select some features as salient.
[src:ritual/aarne-thompson-uther-index] In 2009, describing the motivation for his work, Uther presents several criticisms of the original index.
[src:ritual/aarne-thompson-uther-index] He points out that Thompson's focus on oral tradition sometimes neglects older versions of stories, even when written records exist, and that some included folktale types have dubious importance.
[src:ritual/aarne-thompson-uther-index] In regards to the typological classification, some folklorists and tale comparativists have acknowledged singular tale types that, due to their own characteristics, would merit their own type.
[src:ritual/aarne-thompson-uther-index] Although such tales often have not been listed in the international folktale system, they can exist in regional or national classification systems.
[src:ritual/aarne-thompson-uther-index] In his 2009 critique, Uther finds that the distribution of stories is uneven (with Eastern and Southern European as well as many other regions' folktale types being under-represented).
[src:ritual/aarne-thompson-uther-index] Similarly, Thompson had noted that the tale type index might well be called *The Types of the Folk-Tales of Europe, West Asia, and the Lands Settled by these Peoples*.
[src:ritual/aarne-thompson-uther-index] The ATU folktype index has been criticized for its apparent geographic concentration on Europe and North Africa, showing over-representation of Eurasia and North America.
[src:ritual/aarne-thompson-uther-index] The catalogue appears to ignore or under-represent other regions.
[src:ritual/aarne-thompson-uther-index] Central Asian examples include: Yuri Berezkin's *The captive Khan and the clever daughter-in-law* (and variants); *The travelling girl and her helpful siblings*; and *Woman's magical horse*, as named by researcher Veronica Muskheli of the University of Washington.
[src:ritual/aarne-thompson-uther-index] Author Pete Jordi Wood claims that topics related to homosexuality have been excluded intentionally from the type index.
[src:ritual/aarne-thompson-uther-index] A quantitative study published by folklorist S.
[src:ritual/aarne-thompson-uther-index] Tehrani in 2016, attempted to evaluate the time of emergence for the "Tales of Magic" (ATU 300–ATU 749), based on a phylogenetic model.
[src:ritual/aarne-thompson-uther-index] They found four of them to belong to the Proto-Indo-European stratum of magic tales.
[src:ritual/aarne-thompson-uther-index] Ten more magic tales were found to be current throughout the Western branch of the Indo-European languages, comprising the main European language families derived from PIE (i.e.
[src:ritual/abenaki-mythology] The Abenaki people are an indigenous peoples of the Americas located in the Northeastern Woodlands region.
[src:ritual/abenaki-mythology] Their religious beliefs are part of the *Midewiwin* tradition, with ceremonies led by medicine keepers, called *Medeoulin* or *Mdawinno*.
[src:ritual/abenaki-mythology] In Abenaki mythology the highest deity is Gici Niwaskw, also referred to by the titles of Tabaldak or Dabaldak, meaning Lord, and Niwaskowôgan, meaning Great Spirit.
[src:ritual/abenaki-mythology] According to the creation myth, there existed no sound or color prior until Gici Niwaskw desired it and began the process of creating the world.
[src:ritual/abenaki-mythology] To do so he called forth a giant turtle, called Tolba, from the primordial waters, crafting the land on top of Tolba's shell and the clouds above that.
[src:ritual/abenaki-mythology] After this creation the Great Spirit fell asleep and began to dream of every creature and plant to ever exist, waking to discover that his dreams had become reality as he had slept.
[src:ritual/abenaki-mythology] Thus the newly created world was populated by living things.
[src:ritual/abenaki-mythology] The main character noted for being responsible for the care of Gici Niwaskw's creations and the transition between the three ages is Gluskab, known by different names such as Glooscap, Glooskap, Gluskabe, and Klooskomba throughout the various Abenaki branch tribes.
[src:ritual/abenaki-mythology] While not a full deity within the mythology Gluskab is characterized as a being with supernatural powers who uses them to make life easier for humankind while maintaining a fondness for trickery and playing pranks on people.
[src:ritual/abenaki-mythology] One of Gluskab's many feats was tricking the great eagle Pamola, who creates wind by beating his wings, to allow him to tie his wings, and freeing them once the eagle promised to only cause storms sometimes.
[src:ritual/abenaki-mythology] Gluskab is also credited with shrinking beavers to their modern size, as during the Ancient Age they were larger than humans.
[src:ritual/abenaki-mythology] He did this by petting them on their heads, and with each pet, he used his magic to cause them to grow smaller and smaller.
[src:ritual/abenaki-mythology] The most common tale was of Gluskab turning the syrup within maple trees to sap.
[src:ritual/abenaki-mythology] Initially, syrup could be found directly in maple trees, so the humans sat under the trees all day and let the sweet treat drip directly into their mouths, leaving the fields untended and homes unkempt.
[src:ritual/abenaki-mythology] Gluskab poured water into the maple trees to dilute the syrup, which meant that humans could no longer have maple syrup without collecting it and boiling it down for much less than they had gathered.
[src:ritual/abenaki-mythology] Thus Gluskab ensured humans would not grow lazy in their lives.
[src:ritual/abenaki-mythology] In some versions of his story, Gluskab is noted as being the twin of Malsum or Malsumis, a more malevolent being that seeks to make life harder for humans rather than easier.
[src:ritual/abenaki-mythology] However, there is some doubt of whether this version actually comes from Abenaki mythology or if it is a misattributed Iroquois tale, as there exists only one known source for it within the Abenaki tribes and no wider knowledge of it within them.
[src:ritual/abenaki-mythology] Since the creation, it is believed by the Abenaki that the world has gone through three separate ages, defined by humanity and its relationship with the other animals.
[src:ritual/abenaki-mythology] First, there is the Ancient Age, where humans and animals are viewed as equal, followed by the Golden Age, where humans begin to separate themselves from being like the other animals.
[src:ritual/abenaki-mythology] Finally, there is the Present Age, which is marked by the current status of humans being completely separate from the rest of the animals.
[src:ritual/abkhaz-traditional-religion] According to the 2003 census, 8% of the population of Abkhazia adheres to Abkhaz neopaganism.
[src:ritual/abkhaz-traditional-religion] On 3 August 2012 the Council of Priests of Abkhazia was formally constituted in Sukhumi.
[src:ritual/abkhaz-traditional-religion] The possibility of making the Abkhaz native religion one of the state religions was discussed in the following months.
[src:ritual/abkhaz-traditional-religion] The traditional Abkhaz religion was actually never completely wiped out; circles of priests, whose activity was kept secret, passed on traditional knowledge and rites in the times when Christianity and Islam became dominant in the region, and later in Soviet times of anti-religion.
[src:ritual/abkhaz-traditional-religion] Such priests continued the worship of deities such as the thunder god Afy and the supreme god Antsua.
[src:ritual/abkhaz-traditional-religion] A turning point for the revival of the Abkhaz native religion came with the Georgian–Abkhazian conflict.
[src:ritual/abkhaz-traditional-religion] With tensions growing, more and more Abkhazians began associating Orthodox Christianity with the Georgians, and chose to reject it, turning to the native gods.
[src:ritual/abkhaz-traditional-religion] The eventual victory of Abkhazia in the 1992–93 war with Georgia catalyzed the Neopagan revival.
[src:ritual/abkhaz-traditional-religion] Many Abkhaz believe that their national god Dydrypsh awarded them the victory.
[src:ritual/abkhaz-traditional-religion] Since then the Abkhaz native religion has been protected by Abkhaz authorities.
[src:ritual/abkhaz-traditional-religion] Government officials took part in a bull sacrifice in October 1993 celebrated to thank the Lord Dydrypsh for the victory over the Georgians, and since then they regularly take part in worship rituals.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] The religions of this set share doctrinal, historical, and geographic overlap that contrast them with Indian religions, Iranian religions, and East Asian religions, although some smaller Abrahamic religions, such as the Baha'i Faith, are also Iranian religions.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Judaism, Christianity, and Islam, are the three largest Abrahamic religions, with Christianity and Islam being followed and adhered to by around half of the world's population.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] However, the term has been criticized by some scholars for reportedly oversimplifying cultural and doctrinal nuances between the different religions.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] The term *Abrahamic religions* (and its variations) is a collective religious descriptor for similar and closely related elements shared by Judaism, Christianity, and Islam, as well as the smaller religions such as the Baháʼí Faith, the Druze faith, Rastafari, and Samaritanism.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] It features prominently in interfaith dialogue and civil discourse, as well as academic discourse.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] The term appears for the first time in the second half of the 20th century.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Although historically the term *Abrahamic religions* was limited to just Judaism, Christianity, and Islam, restricting the category to these three religions has come under criticism.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] The late-19th-century Baháʼí Faith has been characterized as Abrahamic, as it is a monotheistic religion that recognizes its own descent from Abraham.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] The figure of Abraham is suggested as a common ground for Judaism, Christianity, Islam, as well as Samaritanism, the Druze Faith, the Baha'i Faith, and Rastafari and a hypothesized eschatological reconciliation of the seven religions.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Commonalities may include creation, revelation, and redemption, but such shared concepts vary significantly between and within the Abrahamic religions themselves.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Proponents of the term argue that all seven religions are united through the deity worshipped by Abraham.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] The Catholic scholar of Islam Louis Massignon argued that the phrase "Abrahamic religion" means that the religions come from one spiritual source.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] The modern term comes from the plural form of a Quranic reference to *dīn Ibrāhīm* ("religion of Abraham").
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] In Christianity, Paul the Apostle, in Romans 4:11–12, refers to Abraham as "father of all", including those "who have faith, circumcised or uncircumcised." From its founding, Islam likewise conceived of itself as the "religion of Abraham".
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] The Bahá’í scriptures state that the religion's founder, Baháʼu'lláh, descended from Abraham through his wife Keturah's sons.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] The appropriateness of grouping Judaism, Christianity, and Islam as "Abrahamic religions" and related terms has been challenged.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Adam Dodds argues that the term "Abrahamic faiths", while helpful, can be misleading, as it conveys an unspecified historical and theological commonality that is problematic on closer examination.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] While there is commonality among the religions, their shared ancestry is mainly peripheral to their respective foundational theological claims, practices, and cultures, concealing irreconcilable differences.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] The common Christian doctrines of Jesus's Incarnation, the Trinity, and the resurrection of Jesus, for example, are accepted in neither Judaism nor Islam.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Jewish tradition claims that the Twelve Tribes of Israel are descended from Abraham through his son Isaac and grandson Jacob, whose sons formed the nation of the Israelites in Canaan.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] In its early stages, the Israelite religion (Yahwism) shares traits with the Canaanite religions of the Bronze Age; by the Iron Age, it had become distinct from other Canaanite religions as it shed polytheism for monolatry.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] They understood their relationship with their god, Yahweh, as a covenant and that the deity promised Abraham a permanent homeland.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] The monolatrist nature of Yahwism was further developed in the period following the Babylonian captivity, eventually emerging as a firm religious movement of monotheism.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] With the Fall of Babylon, Judaism incorporated concepts such as messianism, belief in free will and judgement after death, conception of heaven and hell, angels and demons, among others, into their belief-system.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Christianity traces back their origin to the 1st century and refers to themselves as a continuation of Judaism (commonly referred to as the old covenant) initially led by Jesus.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] His followers viewed him as the Messiah, as in the Confession of Peter; after his crucifixion and death they came to view him as God incarnate, who was resurrected and will return at the end of time to judge the living and the dead and create an eternal Kingdom of God.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] In the 1st century AD, under the Apostles of Jesus of Nazareth; Christianity spread widely.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Paul the Apostle interpreted the role of Abraham differently from the Jews of his time.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] While for the Jews, Abraham was considered a loyal monotheist in a polytheistic environment, Paul celebrates Abraham as a man who found faith in God before adhering to religious law.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] In contrast to Judaism, adherence to religious law becomes associated with idolatry.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] While Christians fashioned their religion around Jesus of Nazareth, the siege of Jerusalem (70 CE), forced Jews to reconcile their belief-system with the destruction of the Second Temple and associated rituals.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] At this time, both Judaism and Christianity had to systematize their scriptures and beliefs, resulting in competing theologies both claiming Abrahamic heritage.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Christians could hardly dismiss the Hebrew scriptures as Jesus himself refers to them according to Christian reports, and parallels between Jesus and the Biblical stories of *creation* and *redemption* starting with Abraham in the *Book of Genesis*.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] The distant God asserted by Jesus according to the Christians, created a form of dualism between Creator and creation and the doctrine of *Creatio ex nihilo*, which later heavily influenced Jewish and Islamic theology.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] By that, Christians established their own identity, distinct from both Greeks and Jews, as those who venerate and worship the deity of Jesus.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] After several periods of alternating persecution and relative peace *vis-à-vis* the Roman authorities under different administrations, Christianity became the state church of the Roman Empire in 380, but has been split into various churches from its beginning.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] An attempt was made by the Byzantine Empire to unify Christendom, but this formally failed with the East–West Schism of 1054.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] In the 16th century, the birth and growth of Protestantism during the Reformation further split Christianity into many denominations.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Christianity remains culturally diverse in its Western and Eastern branches, Christianity played a prominent role in the development of Western civilization.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Islam is based on the teachings of the Quran.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Although it considers Muhammad to be the Seal of the prophets, Islam teaches that every prophet preached Islam, as the word *Islam* means submission, the main concept preached by all prophets.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] The Quran also mentions God having revealed the Scrolls of Abraham and the Scrolls of Moses.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Islamic tradition claims that twelve Arab tribes known as the Ishmaelites are descended from Abraham through his son Ishmael in the Arabian Peninsula.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] The relationship between Islamic and Hebrew scriptures and New Testament differs significantly from the relationship between the New Testament and the Hebrew Bible.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] In the 7th century AD, Islam was founded by Muhammad in the Arabian Peninsula; it spread widely through the early Muslim conquests, shortly after his death.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Islam understands its form of "Abrahamic monotheism" as preceding both Judaism and Christianity, and in contrast with Arabian Henotheism.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] The teachings of the Quran are believed by Muslims to be the direct and final revelation and words of God.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Islam, like Christianity, is a universal religion (i.e. membership is open to anyone).
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Like Judaism, it has a strictly unitary conception of God, called *tawhid* or "strict monotheism".
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] The story of the creation of the world in the Quran is elaborated less extensively than in the Hebrew scripture, emphasizing the transcendence and universality of God, instead.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] According to the Quran, God says *kun fa-yakūnu*.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] The Quran describes God as the creator of "heavens and earth", to emphasize that it is a universal God and not a local Arabian deity.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Samaritanism is considered by some fringe Jewish and Christian apologetics to be a sect which diverged from Judaism in the 6th to 3rd centuries BCE.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] There is growing archaeological, DNA testing, and textual evidence in modern times which has proved the status of the Israelite Samaritans as an independent Abrahamic ethnoreligion and indigenous people of the Levant in their own right.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] The evidence has authenticated their claim to a legal religious status.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Some sources consider Mandaeism to be an Abrahamic religion – however, that classification is controversial, given that Mandaeism does not accept Abraham as a prophet, despite revering as prophets several other figures from the Jewish scriptures.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] On the contrary, the Mandaeans believe that Abraham was originally a priest of their religion, but became an apostate from it.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Druze is another religion which emerged from Islam in the 11th century, and hence is sometimes also considered an Abrahamic religion.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Yazidism, another Kurdish religion, is considered a syncretic religion and shares elements with Shia Islam, Mandaeism, Christianity, and Judaism, including a belief in Adam and Abraham.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] It has also been influenced by Islamic mysticism and Gnostic Christianity.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] In Yazidism, the prophet Abraham is invoked during prayers before a meal, especially ritual meals.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] A number of sources include the Baháʼí Faith, established in the 19th century, since it historically emerged in an Islamic milieu, and shares several beliefs with the Abrahamic faiths, including monotheism and recognising Jewish, Christian and Islamic figures as prophets.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Some scholars include Bábism, a 19th-century movement and precursor to the Baháʼí Faith.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Rastafari, an Afrocentric religion which emerged from Christianity in 1930s Jamaica, is also sometimes classified as Abrahamic, in particular due to its monotheism and use of the Bible as scripture.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Abrahamic religions agree upon the createdness of the universe by God, who is conceived of as eternal, omnipotent, and omniscient.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] All three identify the creator of the universe with the God revealed to Abraham.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] However, they differ on how to conceptualize God.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Christianity proposes God's utter transcendence and that an intermediary — such as an incarnation of God — is required to bridge the gap between God and humans.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] According to Islam, God is knowable through his creation, metaphorical stories of the prophets stored in the Quran, and signs in nature.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Christianity proposes God's personhood in the form of a Son of God as an aspect of the Divinity as formulated in the doctrine of the Trinity.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] In contrast, God in Islam is less personal than described in the Judeo-Christian tradition, and more of a mysterious power behind all aspects of the universe.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Their religious texts feature many of the same figures, histories, and places, although they often present them with different roles, perspectives, and meanings.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Believers who agree on these similarities and the common Abrahamic origin tend to also be more positive towards other Abrahamic groups.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Religious law in Judaism and Samaritanism commands that males be circumcised when they are eight days old, as does the *sunnah* ('tradition') in Islam.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Despite its common practice in Muslim-majority nations, circumcision is considered to be *sunnah* and not required for a life directed by Allah.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Although there is some debate within Islam over whether it is a religious requirement or mere recommendation, circumcision (called *khitan*) is practiced nearly universally by Muslim males.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Today, many Christian denominations are neutral about ritual male circumcision, neither requiring it for religious observance nor forbidding it for cultural or other reasons.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Western Christianity replaced the custom of male circumcision with the ritual of baptism, a ceremony which varies according to the doctrine of the denomination, but it generally includes immersion, aspersion, or anointment with water.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] The Early Church, as recorded in Acts 15 at the Council of Jerusalem, decided that Gentile Christians are not required to undergo circumcision.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] The Council of Florence in the 15th century prohibited it.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Paragraph #2297 of the Catechism of the Catholic Church calls non-medical amputation or mutilation immoral.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] By the 21st century, the Catholic Church had adopted a neutral position on the practice, as long as it was not practised as an initiation ritual.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Catholic scholars make various arguments in support of the idea that this policy is not in contradiction with the previous edicts.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] The New Testament, in Acts 15, records that Christianity did not require circumcision.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Coptic Christians practice circumcision as a rite of passage.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] The Eritrean Orthodox Church and the Ethiopian Orthodox Tewahedo Church calls for circumcision, with near-universal prevalence among Orthodox men in Ethiopia.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Many countries with majorities of Christian adherents in Europe and Latin America have low circumcision rates.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] In contrast, both religious and non-religious circumcision is widely practiced in many predominantly Christian countries and among Christian communities in the Anglosphere countries, Oceania, South Korea, the Philippines, the Middle East and Africa.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Countries such as the United States, the Philippines, Australia (albeit primarily in the older generations), Canada, Cameroon, Democratic Republic of the Congo, Ethiopia, Equatorial Guinea, Ghana, Nigeria, Kenya, and many other African Christian countries have high circumcision rates.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Circumcision is near universal in the Christian countries of Oceania.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] In some African and Eastern Christian denominations male circumcision is an integral or established practice, and require that their male members undergo circumcision.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Coptic Christianity and Ethiopian Orthodoxy and Eritrean Orthodoxy still observe male circumcision and practice circumcision as a rite of passage.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Male circumcision is also widely practiced among Christians from Egypt, Syria, Lebanon, Jordan, Palestine, Israel, and North Africa.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Male circumcision is among the rites of Islam and is part of the *fitrah*, or the innate disposition and natural character and instinct of the human creation.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Although circumcision is widely practiced among the Druze, it is performed as a cultural tradition and has no religious significance in the Druze faith.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Some Druze do not circumcise their male children, and refuse to observe this "common Muslim practice".
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Circumcision is not a religious practice of the Bahá'í Faith, and the decision is left to the parents.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Judaism accepts converts, but has had no explicit missionaries since the end of the Second Temple period.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Judaism states that non-Jews can achieve righteousness by following Noahide Laws, a set of moral imperatives that, according to the Talmud, were given by God as a binding set of laws for the "children of Noah"—that is, all of humanity.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] It is believed that as much as 10% of the Roman Empire followed Judaism either as fully ritually obligated Jews or the simpler rituals required of non-Jewish members of that faith.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] In the U.S., as of 2003, 28% of married Jews were married to non-Jews.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Many Christian organizations, especially Protestant churches, send missionaries to non-Christian communities throughout the world.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Forced conversions to Catholicism have happened at various points throughout history.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Forced conversions to Protestantism has occurred as well, notably during the Reformation, especially in England and Ireland (see recusancy and Popish plot).
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Forced conversions are now condemned as sinful by major denominations such as the Roman Catholic Church, which officially states that forced conversions pollute the Christian religion and offend human dignity, so that past or present offences are regarded as a scandal (a cause of unbelief).
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] According to Pope Paul VI, "It is one of the major tenets of Catholic doctrine that man's response to God in faith must be free: no one, therefore, is to be forced to embrace the Christian faith against his own will." The Roman Catholic Church has declared that Catholics should fight anti-Semitism.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Islam encourages proselytism in various forms.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Dawah is an important Islamic concept that denotes the preaching of Islam.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Da‘wah literally means "issuing a summons" or "making an invitation".
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] A Muslim who practices da‘wah, either as a religious worker or in a volunteer community effort, is called a dā‘ī, plural du‘āt.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] A dā‘ī is thus a person who invites people to understand Islam through a dialogical process and may be categorized in some cases as the Islamic equivalent of a missionary, as one who invites people to the faith, to the prayer, or to Islamic life.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Some pursue Islamic studies specifically to perform Da'wah.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Mosques and other Islamic centers sometimes actively spread Da'wah, similar to evangelical churches.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Others consider being open to the public and answering questions to be Da'wah.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Recalling Muslims to the faith and expanding their knowledge can also be considered Da'wah.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] In Islamic theology, the purpose of Da'wah is to invite people, both Muslims and non-Muslims, to understand the commandments of God as expressed in the Quran and the Sunnah of the Prophet, as well as to inform them about Muhammad.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Da'wah produces converts to Islam, which in turn grows the size of the Muslim Ummah, or community of Muslims.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] While there were instances of forced conversions to Islam, these were neither the norm nor part of a systematic strategy of expansion.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Many Muslim rulers practiced religious pluralism, and the Quran explicitly prohibits compulsion in matters of faith.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Most conversions to Islam occurred gradually, driven by social, cultural, and economic influences rather than coercion.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] However, forcible conversion continues to be practiced in parts of the Islamic world.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Christianity is the largest Abrahamic religion with about 2.5 billion adherents, called Christians, constituting about 31.1% of the world's population.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] Islam is the second largest Abrahamic religion, as well as the fastest-growing Abrahamic religion in recent decades.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] It has about 2.0 billion adherents, called Muslims, constituting about 24.1% of the world's population.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] The third largest Abrahamic religion is Judaism with about 14.1 million adherents, called Jews.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] The Baháʼí Faith has over 8 million adherents, making it the fourth largest Abrahamic religion, and the fastest growing religion across the 20th century, usually at least twice the rate of population growth.
[src:ritual/abrahamic-religions] The Druze faith has between one million and nearly two million adherents.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Four communities make up the village of Acoma Pueblo: Sky City (Old Acoma), Acomita, Anzac, and McCartys.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] These communities are located near the expansive Albuquerque metropolitan area, which includes several large cities and towns, including neighboring Laguna Pueblo.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The Acoma Pueblo tribe is a federally recognized tribal entity, whose historic land of Acoma Pueblo totaled roughly 5,000,000 acres (2,000,000 ha).
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Today, much of the Acoma community is primarily within the Acoma Indian Reservation.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Acoma Pueblo is a National Historic Landmark.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] According to the 2010 United States Census, 4,989 people identified as Acoma.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The Acoma have continuously occupied the area where Acoma Pueblo is situated for over 2,000 years.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Acoma Pueblo is one of the oldest continuously inhabited communities in the United States.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The English name *Acoma* was borrowed from Spanish *Ácoma* (1583) or *Acóma* (1598).
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The Spanish name was borrowed from the Acoma word *ʔáák’u̓u̓m̓é* meaning 'person from Acoma Pueblo'.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] *ʔáák’u̓u̓m̓é* itself is derived from *ʔáák’u* (singular; plural: *ʔaak’u̓u̓m̓e̓e̓ʈʂʰa*).
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The name does not have any meaning in the modern Acoma language.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Some tribal authorities connect it to the similar word *háák’u*, 'preparedness, place of preparedness', and suggest that this might be the origin of the name.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Other tribal elders assert that it means 'place that always was', while outsiders say it means 'people of the white rock'.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The Acoma are called *ʔáák’u* ([ʔɑ́ːk'ù] in Western Keresan, *Hakukya* in Zuni, and *Haak’oh* in Navajo.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The Acoma language is classified in the western division of the Keresan languages.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] In contemporary Acoma Pueblo culture, most people speak both Acoma and English, elders speak an endangered indigenous variant of New Mexican Spanish.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Pueblo people descend from Ancestral Puebloans, Mogollon, and other precontact peoples.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] These influences are seen in the architecture, farming style, and artistry of the Acoma.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] In the 13th century, the Ancestral Puebloans abandoned their canyon homelands due to climate change and social upheaval.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] For more than two centuries, there were migrations in the area.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The Acoma Pueblo emerged by the 13th century.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] However, the Acoma themselves say the Sky City Pueblo was established in the 11th century, with brick buildings as early as 1144 on the mesa.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Evidence for their antiquity is the unique lack of adobe in their construction.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Acoma Pueblo is one of the earliest continuously inhabited communities in the United States.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The Pueblo is situated on a 365-foot (111 m) mesa, about 60 miles (97 km) west of Albuquerque, New Mexico.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The isolation and location of the Pueblo has sheltered the community for more than 1,200 years as they sought protection from the raids of the neighboring Navajo and Apache peoples.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Estevanico, a slave and the first person of African descent to explore North America, was the first non-Indian to visit Acoma and reported it to Marcos de Niza, who related the information to the viceroy of New Spain after the end of his expedition.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Acoma was called the independent Kingdom of Hacus.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] He called the Acoma people *encaconados,* which meant that they had turquoise hanging from their ears and noses.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] It is believed Coronado's expedition were the first Europeans to encounter the Acoma (Estevan was a native Moroccan).
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Alvarado reported that first the Acoma refused entry even after persuasions, but after Alvarado showed threats of an attack, the Acoma guards welcomed the Spaniards peacefully, noting that they and their horses were tired.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The encounter shows that the Acoma had clothing made of deerskin, buffalo hide, and woven cotton, as well as turquoise jewelry, domestic turkeys, bread, pine nuts, and maize.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The village seemed to contain about 200 men.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Acoma was next visited by the Spanish 40 years later in 1581 by Fray Agustín Rodríguez and Francisco Sánchez Chamuscado, with 12 soldiers, 3 other friars, and 13 others, including Indian servants.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The Acoma at this time were reported to be somewhat defensive and fearful.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] This response may have been due to the knowledge of the Spanish enslavement of other Indians to work in silver mines in the area.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] However, eventually the Rodríguez and Chamuscado party convinced them to trade goods for food.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The Spaniard reports say the pueblo had about 500 houses of either three or four stories high.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] In 1582, Acoma was visited again by Antonio de Espejo for three months.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The Acoma were reported to be wearing mantas.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Espejo also noted irrigation in Acomita, the farming village in the north valley near San Jose River, which was two leagues from the mesa.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] He saw evidence of intertribal trade with "mountain Querechos".
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Acoma oral history does not confirm this trade but only tells of common messengers to and from the mesa and Acomita, McCartys Village, and Seama.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Juan de Oñate intended to colonize New Mexico starting from 1595 (he formally held the area by April 1598).
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The Acoma warrior Zutacapan heard of this plan and warned the mesa and organized a defense.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] However, a pueblo elder, Chumpo, dissuaded war, partly to prevent deaths and partly based on Zutancalpo's (Zutacapan's son) mentioning of the widespread belief that the Spaniards were immortal.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Thus, when Oñate visited on October 27, 1598, Acoma met him peacefully, with no resistance to Oñate's demand of surrender and obedience reported.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Oñate demonstrated his military power by firing a gun salute.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Zutacapan offered to meet Oñate formally in the religious kiva, which is traditionally used as the place to make sacred oaths and pledges.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] However, Oñate was scared of death and in suspicious ignorance of Acoma customs refused to enter via ladder from the roof into the dark kiva chambers.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Purguapo was another Acoma man out of four chosen for Spaniard negotiations.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Soon after Oñate's departure, Gaspar Pérez de Villagrá visited Acoma by himself with a dog and a horse and asked for other supplies.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Villagrá refused to get off his horse and left to follow Oñate's party.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] However, Zutacapan convinced him to return to receive supplies.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] In questioning by Zutacapan, Villagrá said that 103 armed men were two days away from Acoma.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Zutacapan then told Villagrá to leave Acoma.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] On December 1, 1598, Juan de Zaldívar, Oñate's nephew, reached Acoma with 20–30 men and peacefully traded with them and had to wait some days for their order of ground corn.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] On December 4, Zaldívar went with 16 armored men to Acoma to find out about the corn.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Zutacapan met them and directed them to the homes with the corn.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Zaldívar's people then divided into groups to collect the corn.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The traditional oral Acoma narrative tells that a group attacked some Acoma women, leading Acoma warriors to retaliate.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The Spanish documents do not report an attack on the women and say that the division of the men was a reaction to Zutacapan's plan to kill Zaldívar's party.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The Acoma killed 12 of the Spaniards, including Zaldívar.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Five men escaped, although one died from jumping over the citadel, leaving four to escape with the remaining camp.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] On December 20, 1598, Oñate learned of Zaldívar's death and, after receiving encouraging advice from the friars, planned an attack in revenge, as well to teach a lesson to other pueblos.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Acomas requested help from other tribes to defend against the Spanish.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Among the leaders were Gicombo, Popempol, Chumpo, Calpo, Buzcoico, Ezmicaio, and Bempol (a recruited Apache war leader).
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] On January 21, 1599, Vicente de Zaldívar (Juan de Zaldívar's brother) reached Acoma with 70 soldiers.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The Acoma Massacre started the next day and lasted for three days.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] On January 23, men were able to climb the southern mesa unnoticed by Acoma guards and breach the pueblo.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The Spanish dragged a cannon through the streets, toppling adobe walls and burning most of the village, killing 800 people (decimating 20% of the 4,000 population) and imprisoning approximately 500 others.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Almost all of the remaining inhabitants were enslaved or left the town.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The pueblo surrendered at noon on January 24.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The Spanish amputated the right feet of men over 25 years old, and by some accounts one or more toes of such enslaved men's right feet, and forced them into slavery for 20 years.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] They also took males aged 12–25 and females over 12 away from their parents, putting most of them in slavery for 20 years.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The enslaved Acoma were given to government officials and various missions.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Two other Indian men visiting Acoma at the time had their right hands cut off and were sent back to their respective Pueblos as a warning of the consequences for resisting the Spanish.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] On the north side of the mesa, a row of houses still retains marks from the fire started by a cannon during this Acoma War Oñate was later exiled from New Mexico for mismanagement, false reporting, and cruelty by Philip III of Spain.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Survivors of the Acoma Massacre rebuilt their community between 1599 and 1620.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The town remained uninhabited for several months, out of fear of more attacks, until it began to be rebuilt in December 1599.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Oñate forced the Acoma and other local Indians to pay taxes in crops, cotton, and labor.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Spanish rule also brought Catholic missionaries into the area.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The Spanish renamed the pueblos with the names of saints and started to construct churches in them.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] They introduced new crops to the Acoma, including peaches, peppers, and wheat.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] A 1620 royal decree created Spanish civil offices in each pueblo, including Acoma, with an appointed governor to take command.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] In 1680, the Pueblo Revolt took place, with Acoma participating.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The revolt brought refugees from other pueblos.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Those who eventually left Acoma moved elsewhere to form Laguna Pueblo.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The Acoma suffered high mortality from smallpox epidemics, as they had no immunity to such Eurasian infectious diseases.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] They also suffered raiding from the Apache, Comanche, and Ute.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] On occasion, the Acoma would side with the Spanish to fight against these nomadic tribes.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Forced to formally adopt Catholicism, the Acoma proceeded to practice their traditional religion in secrecy, and combined elements of both in a syncretic blend.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Intermarriage and interaction became common among the Acoma, other pueblos, and Hispanic villages.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] These communities would intermingle in a kind of creolization to form the culture of New Mexico.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Between 1629 and 1641 Father Juan Ramirez oversaw construction of the San Estevan Del Rey Mission Church.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The Acoma were ordered to build the church, moving 20,000 short tons (18,000 t) of adobe, straw, sandstone, and mud to the mesa for the church walls.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Ponderosa pine was brought in by community members from Mount Taylor, over 40 miles (64 km) away.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The 6,000 square feet (560 m2) church has an altar flanked by 60 feet (18 m)-high wood pillars.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] These are hand carved in red and white designs, representing Christian and Indigenous beliefs.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The Acoma know their ancestors' hands built this structure, and they consider it a cultural treasure.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] In 1970, it was placed on the National Register of Historic Places.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] In 2007, the mission church was designated a National Trust Historic Site, the only Native American site in that ranking as identified by the National Trust for Historic Preservation, a non-profit organization.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] During the 19th century, the Acoma people, while trying to uphold traditional life, also adopted aspects of the once-rejected Spanish culture and religion.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] By the 1880s, railroads brought increased numbers of settlers and ended the pueblos' isolation.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] In the 1920s, the All Indian Pueblo Council gathered for the first time in more than 300 years.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Responding to congressional interest in appropriating Pueblo lands, the U.S.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Congress passed the Pueblo Lands Act in 1924.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Despite successes in retaining their land, the Acoma had difficulty in preserving their cultural traditions in the 20th century.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Protestant missionaries established schools in the area, and the Bureau of Indian Affairs forced Acoma children into boarding schools.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] By 1922, most children from the community were in boarding schools, where they were forced to use English and practice Christianity.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Several generations became cut off from their culture and language, with harsh effects on their families and societies.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] About 300 two- and three-story adobe buildings stand on the mesa, with exterior ladders used to access the upper levels where residents live.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Access to the mesa is by a road blasted into the rock face during the 1950s, navigable by car and bus.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Footpaths down the mesa can still be used.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Approximately 30 or so people live permanently on the mesa, with the population increasing on the weekends, as family members come to visit, and tourists, some 55,000 annually, visit for the day.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Acoma Pueblo has no electricity, running water, or sewage disposal.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Contemporary Acoma culture remains relatively closed.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] According to the 2000 United States census, 4,989 people identify themselves as Acoma.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Historically Acoma was governed a *cacique* and war captain, who would serve until their deaths.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Both individuals maintained strong religious connections to their work, representing the theocracy of Acoma governance.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The Spanish imposed a group to oversee the Pueblo, but their power was not taken seriously by the Acoma.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The Spanish group would work with external situations and comprised a governor, two lieutenant governors, and a council.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The Acoma also participated in the All Indian Pueblo Council, which started in 1598, arose again in the 20th century, and is active today.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The cacique is still active in the community and is from the Antelope clan.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The cacique appoints tribal council members, staff, and the governor.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] In 2011, Acoma Pueblo and the Pueblo of Santa Clara were victims of heavy flooding.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] New Mexico supplied more than $1 million to fund emergency preparedness and damage repair for victims, and Governor Susana Martinez requested additional funding from the Federal Emergency Management Agency.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The Acoma control their Indian reservation on approximately 500,000 acres (200,000 ha) of their traditional land.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Mesas, valleys, hills, and arroyos dot the landscape that averages about 7,000 feet (2,100 m) in altitude, with about 10 inches (250 mm) of rain each year.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Since 1977, the Acoma have increased their domain through several land purchases.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] On the reservation, only tribal citizens may own land and almost all enrolled citizens live on the property.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The **Pueblo of Acoma** () is an of the Acoma Pueblo peoples located in parts of Cibola, Socorro, and Catron counties, in New Mexico, the Southwestern United States.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The reservation borders the Laguna Indian Reservation to the east and is near El Malpais National Monument due west.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The total number of tribal citizens is about 6,000.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] According to 2020 census, 3,230 people lived on the reservation.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Tribal citizens live both on the reservation and outside it.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Acoma Pueblo (Sky City) is the heart of the reservation and is one of the oldest continuously inhabited places in the United States.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Acoma Pueblo has three rows of three-story, apartment-style buildings, which face south on top of the mesa.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The buildings are constructed from adobe brick, with beams across the roof that were covered with poles, brush, and then plaster.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The roof for one level would serve as the floor for another.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Each level is connected to others by ladders, serving as a unique defensive aid; the ladders are the only way to enter the buildings, as the traditional design has no windows or doors.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The lower levels of the buildings were used for storage.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Baking ovens are outside the buildings, with water being collected from two natural cisterns.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Acoma also has seven rectangular kivas and a village plaza, which serves as the spiritual center for the village.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] About 20 matrilineal clans were recognized by the Acoma.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Traditional child rearing involved very little discipline .
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Couples were generally monogamous, and divorce was rare.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] A quick burial followed death, then four days and nights of vigil.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Women wore cotton dresses and sandals or high moccasin boots.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Men wore cotton kilts and leather sandals.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Rabbit and deer skin was also used for clothing and robes.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] In the 17th century, horses were introduced to the Pueblo by the Spanish.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Education was overseen by kiva headmen, who taught about human behavior, spirit and body, astrology, ethics, child psychology, oratory, history, dance, and music.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Since the 1970s, Acoma Pueblo has retained control over education services, which have been keys in maintaining traditional and contemporary lifestyles.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] They share a high school with Laguna Pueblo.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Alcoholism, drug use, and other health issues are prominent on the reservation and Indian Health Service hospitals and native healers cooperate to battle health problems.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The community is served by the Acoma-Canoncito-Laguna (ACL) Hospital run by the Indian Health Services and located in Acoma.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Traditional Acoma religion stresses harmony between life and nature.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The Sun is a representative of the Creator deity.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Mountains surrounding the community, the Sun above, and the Earth below help to balance and define the Acoma world.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Traditional religious ceremonies may revolve around the weather, including seeking to ensure healthy rainfall.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The Pueblos also had one or more kivas, which served as religious chambers.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The leader of each Pueblo would serve as the community religious leader, or *cacique*.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The cacique would observe the Sun and use it as a guide for scheduling ceremonies, some which were kept secret.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Many Acoma are Catholic, but blend aspects of Catholicism and their traditional religion.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] In September, the Acoma honor their patron saint, Saint Stephen.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] For feast day, the mesa is opened to the public for the celebration.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] More than 2,000 pilgrims attend the San Esteban Festival.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The celebration begins at San Esteban Del Rey Mission, and a carved pine effigy of Saint Stephen is removed from the altar and carried into the main plaza with people chanting, shooting rifles, and ringing steeple bells.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The procession then proceeds past the cemetery, down narrow streets, and to the plaza.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Upon arriving at the plaza, the effigy is placed in a shrine lined with woven blankets and guarded by two Acoma men.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] A celebration follows with dancing and feasting.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] During the festival, vendors sell goods, such as traditional pottery and cuisine.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Before contact with the Spanish, Acoma people primarily ate corn, beans, and squash.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] *Mut-tze-nee* was a popular thin corn bread.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] They also raised turkeys, tobacco, and sunflowers.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The Acoma hunted antelope, deer, and rabbits.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Wild seeds, berries, nuts, and other foods were gathered.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] After 1700, new foods were noted in the historical record.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Staples included blue corn drink, pudding, corn mush, corn balls, wheat cake, peach-bark drink, paper bread, flour bread, wild berries, and prickly pear fruit.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] After contact with the Spanish, goats, horses, sheep and donkeys were raised.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] In contemporary Acoma, other foods are also popular, such as apple pastries, corn tamales, green-chili stew with lamb, fresh corn, and wheat pudding with brown sugar.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Irrigation techniques such as dams and terraces were used for agriculture.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Farming tools were made of wood and stone.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Harvested corn would be ground with hands and mortar.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] A list of Acoma Pueblo ethnobotany shows 68 documented plant uses.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Swank published a Master's thesis titled "The Ethnobotany of the Acoma and Laguna Indians," containing short sections on the Puebloans' history, culture and mythology as well as an extensive treatment of plant uses and names.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Historically, engagements in warfare were common for Acoma, like other Pueblos.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Weapons used included war clubs, stones, spears, and darts.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The Acoma later would serve as auxiliaries for forces under Spain and Mexico, fighting against raids and protecting merchants on the Santa Fe Trail.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] After the 19th century, raiding tribes were less of a threat and Acoma military culture began to decline.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The war captain position eventually would change to a civil and religious function.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Historical Acoma economic practices are described as socialistic or communal.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Labor was shared and produce was distributed equally.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Trading networks were extensive, spreading thousands of miles throughout the region.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] During fixed times in the summer and fall, trading fairs were held.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The largest fair was held in Taos by the Comanche.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Nomadic traders would exchange slaves, buckskins, buffalo hide, jerky, and horses.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Pueblo people would trade for copper and shell ornaments, macaw feathers, and turquoise.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Since 1821, the Acoma traded via the Santa Fe Trail.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The arrival of railroads in the 1880s made the Acoma dependent on American-made goods, which suppressed traditional arts such as weaving and pottery.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Today, the Acoma produce a variety of goods.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] They grow alfalfa, oats, wheat, chilies, corn, melon, squash, vegetables, and fruit, and they raise cattle.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] They have natural reserves of gas, geothermal, and coal resources.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Uranium mines in the area provided work for the Acoma until their closings in the 1980s.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] After that, the tribe provided most employment.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] However, high unemployment rates trouble the Pueblo.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The uranium mines left radiation pollution, causing the tribal fishing lake to be drained and some health problems within the community.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Tourism is a major source of income for the tribe.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] In 2008, Pueblo Acoma opened the Sky City Cultural Center and Haak'u Museum at the base of the mesa, replacing the original, which was destroyed by fire in 2000.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The center and museum seek to sustain and preserve Acoma culture.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Films about Acoma history are shown and a café serves traditional foods.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The architecture was inspired by pueblo design and indigenous architectural traditions, with wide doorways in the middle, which in traditional homes make the bringing of supplies easier.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The windowpanes contain flecks of mica, a mineral which is used to create mesa windows.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The complex is also fire resistant, unlike traditional pueblos, and is painted in light pinks and purples to match the landscape surrounding it.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Traditional Acoma artwork is exhibited and demonstrated at the center, including ceramic chimneys crafted on the rooftop.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Acoma Pueblo is open to the public by guided tour from March until October, though June and July have periods of closure for cultural activities.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Photography of the Pueblo and surrounding land is restricted.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Tours and camera permits are purchased at the Sky City Cultural Center.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] While photography is allowed with permit, video recordings, drawings, and sketching are prohibited.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] All photography is forbidden within the church.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The Acoma Pueblo also has a casino and hotel – the Sky City Casino Hotel.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The casino and hotel are alcohol-free and are maintained by the Acoma Business Enterprise, which oversees most Acoma businesses.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] At Acoma, pottery remains one of the most notable artforms.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Men create weavings and silver jewelry, as well.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Acoma pottery dates back more than 1,000 years.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Dense local clay, dug up at a nearby site, is essential to Acoma pottery.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The clay is dried and strengthened by the addition of pulverized pottery shards.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] The pieces then are shaped, painted, and fired.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] Geometric patterns, thunderbirds, and rainbows are traditional designs, which are applied with the spike of a yucca.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] A potter lightly strikes the side of the pot upon completion and holds it to his or her ear; if the pot does not ring, it will crack during firing.
[src:ritual/acoma-pueblo] If this is found, the piece is destroyed and ground into shards for future use.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Unlike guardianship or other systems designed for the care of the young, adoption is intended to effect a permanent change in status and as such requires societal recognition, either through legal or religious sanction.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Historically, some societies have enacted specific laws governing adoption, while others used less formal means (notably contracts that specified inheritance rights and parental responsibilities without an accompanying transfer of filiation).
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Modern systems of adoption, arising in the 20th century, tend to be governed by comprehensive statutes and regulations.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] While the modern form of adoption emerged in the United States, forms of the practice appeared throughout history.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] The Code of Hammurabi, for example, details the rights of adopters and the responsibilities of adopted individuals at length.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] The practice of adoption in ancient Rome is well-documented in the Codex Justinianus.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Markedly different from the modern period, ancient adoption practices put emphasis on the political and economic interests of the adopter, providing a legal tool that strengthened political ties between wealthy families and created male heirs to manage estates.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] The use of adoption by the aristocracy is well-documented: many of Rome's emperors were adopted sons.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Adrogation was a kind of Roman adoption in which the person adopted consented to be adopted by another.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Infant adoption during Antiquity appears rare.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Abandoned children were often picked up for slavery and composed a significant percentage of the Empire's slave supply.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Roman legal records indicate that foundlings were occasionally taken in by families and raised as a son or daughter.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Although not normally adopted under Roman Law, the children, called *alumni*, were reared in an arrangement similar to guardianship, being considered the property of the father who abandoned them.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Other ancient civilizations, notably India and China, used some form of adoption as well.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Evidence suggests the goal of this practice was to ensure the continuity of cultural and religious practices; in contrast to the Western idea of extending family lines.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] In ancient India, adoption was conducted in a limited and highly ritualistic form, so that an adopter might have the necessary funerary rites performed by a son.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] China had a similar idea of adoption with males adopted solely to perform the duties of ancestor worship.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] The practice of adopting the children of family members and close friends was common among the cultures of Polynesia including Hawaii where the custom was referred to as *hānai*.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] The nobility of the Germanic, Celtic, and Slavic cultures that dominated Europe after the decline of the Roman Empire denounced the practice of adoption.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] In medieval society, bloodlines were paramount; a ruling dynasty lacking a "natural-born" heir apparent was replaced, a stark contrast to Roman traditions.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] The evolution of European law reflects this aversion to adoption.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] English common law, for instance, did not permit adoption since it contradicted the customary rules of inheritance.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] In the same vein, France's Napoleonic Code made adoption difficult, requiring adopters to be over the age of 50, sterile, older than the adopted person by at least 15 years, and to have fostered the adoptee for at least six years.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Some adoptions continued to occur, however, but became informal, based on ad hoc contracts.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] For example, in the year 737, in a charter from the town of Lucca, three adoptees were made heirs to an estate.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Like other contemporary arrangements, the agreement stressed the responsibility of the adopted rather than adopter, focusing on the fact that, under the contract, the adoptive father was meant to be cared for in his old age; an idea that is similar to the conceptions of adoption under Roman law.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Europe's cultural makeover marked a period of significant innovation for adoption.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Without support from the nobility, the practice gradually shifted toward abandoned children.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Abandonment levels rose with the fall of the empire and many of the foundlings were left on the doorstep of the Church.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Initially, the clergy reacted by drafting rules to govern the exposing, selling, and rearing of abandoned children.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] The Church's innovation, however, was the practice of oblation, whereby children were dedicated to lay life within monastic institutions and reared within a monastery.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] This created the first system in European history in which abandoned children did not have legal, social, or moral disadvantages.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] As a result, many of Europe's abandoned and orphaned children became alumni of the Church, which in turn took the role of adopter.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Oblation marks the beginning of a shift toward institutionalization, eventually bringing about the establishment of the foundling hospital and orphanage.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] As the idea of institutional care gained acceptance, formal rules appeared about how to place children into families: boys could become apprenticed to an artisan and girls might be married off under the institution's authority.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Institutions informally adopted out children as well, a mechanism treated as a way to obtain cheap labor, demonstrated by the fact that when the adopted died their bodies were returned by the family to the institution for burial.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] This system of apprenticeship and informal adoption extended into the 19th century, today seen as a transitional phase for adoption history.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Under the direction of social welfare activists, orphan asylums began to promote adoptions based on sentiment rather than work; children were placed out under agreements to provide care for them as family members instead of under contracts for apprenticeship.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] The growth of this model is believed to have contributed to the enactment of the first modern adoption law in 1851 by the Commonwealth of Massachusetts, unique in that it codified the ideal of the "best interests of the child".
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Despite its intent, though, in practice, the system operated much the same as earlier incarnations.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] The experience of the Boston Female Asylum (BFA) is a good example, which had up to 30% of its charges adopted out by 1888.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] The next stage of adoption's evolution fell to the emerging nation of the United States.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Rapid immigration and the American Civil War resulted in unprecedented overcrowding of orphanages and foundling homes in the mid-nineteenth century.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Charles Loring Brace, a Protestant minister, became appalled by the legions of homeless waifs roaming the streets of New York City.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Brace considered the abandoned youth, particularly Catholics, to be the most dangerous element challenging the city's order.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] His solution was outlined in *The Best Method of Disposing of Our Pauper and Vagrant Children* (1859), which started the Orphan Train movement.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] The orphan trains eventually shipped an estimated 200,000 children from the urban centers of the East to the nation's rural regions.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] The children were generally indentured, rather than adopted, to families who took them in.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] As in times past, some children were raised as members of the family while others were used as farm laborers and household servants.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] The sheer size of the displacement—one of the largest migrations of children in history—and the degree of exploitation that occurred, gave rise to new agencies and a series of laws that promoted adoption arrangements rather than indenture.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] The hallmark of the period is Minnesota's adoption law of 1917, which mandated investigation of all placements and limited record access to those involved in the adoption.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] During the same period, the Progressive movement swept the United States with a critical goal of ending the prevailing orphanage system.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] As late as 1923, only two percent of children without parental care were in adoptive homes, with the balance in foster arrangements and orphanages.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Less than forty years later, nearly one-third were in adoptive homes.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Nevertheless, the popularity of eugenic ideas in America put up obstacles to the growth of adoption.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] There were grave concerns about the genetic quality of illegitimate and indigent children, perhaps best exemplified by the influential writings of Henry H.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] The period 1945 to 1974, the baby scoop era, saw rapid growth and acceptance of adoption as a means to build a family.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Illegitimate births rose three-fold after World War II, as sexual mores changed.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Simultaneously, the scientific community began to stress the dominance of nurture over genetics, chipping away at eugenic stigmas.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] In this environment, adoption became the obvious solution for infertile couples.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Many of the mothers, however, were forced or coerced into relinquishing their children.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Taken together, these trends resulted in a new American model for adoption.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Following its Roman predecessor, Americans severed the rights of the original parents while making adopters the new parents in the eyes of the law.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] The origin of the move toward secrecy began with Charles Loring Brace, who introduced it to prevent children from the Orphan Trains from returning to or being reclaimed by their parents.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Brace feared the impact of the parents' poverty, in general, and Catholic religion, in particular, on the youth.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] This tradition of secrecy was carried on by the later Progressive reformers when drafting of American laws.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] The number of adoptions in the United States peaked in 1970.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] The years of the late 1960s and early 1970s saw a dramatic change in society's view of illegitimacy and in the legal rights of those born outside of wedlock.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] In response, family preservation efforts grew so that few children born out of wedlock today are adopted.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Ironically, adoption is far more visible and discussed in society today, yet it is less common.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] The American model of adoption eventually proliferated globally.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] England and Wales established their first formal adoption law in 1926.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Sweden made adoptees full members of the family in 1959.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] West Germany enacted its first laws in 1977.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Additionally, the Asian powers opened their orphanage systems to adoption, influenced as they were by Western ideas following colonial rule and military occupation.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] In France, local public institutions accredit candidates for adoption, who can then contact orphanages abroad or ask for the support of NGOs.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] The system does not involve fees, but gives considerable power to social workers whose decisions may restrict adoption to "standard" families (middle-age, medium to high income, heterosexual, Caucasian).
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] The table below provides a snapshot of Western adoption rates.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Adoption in the United States still occurs at rates nearly three times those of its peers even though the number of children awaiting adoption has held steady in recent years, between 100,000 and 125,000 during the period 2009 to 2018.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Contemporary adoption practices can be open or closed.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Adoptions can occur between related or unrelated individuals.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Historically, most adoptions occurred within a family.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] The most recent data from the U.S. indicates that about half of adoptions are currently between related individuals.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] A common example of this is a "step-parent adoption", where the new partner of a parent legally adopts a child from the parent's previous relationship.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Intra-family adoption can also occur through surrender, as a result of parental death, or when the child cannot otherwise be cared for and a family member agrees to take over.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Adoption is not always a voluntary process.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] In some countries, for example in the U.K., one of the main origins of children being placed for adoption is that they have been removed from the birth home, often by a government body such as the local authority.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] There are a number of reasons why children are removed including abuse and neglect, which can have a lasting impact on the adoptee.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Social workers in many cases will be notified of a safeguarding concern in relation to a child and will make enquiries into the child's well-being.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Social workers will often seek means of keeping a child together with the birth family, for example, by providing additional support to the family before considering removal of a child.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] A court of law will often then make decisions regarding the child's future, for example, whether they can return to the birth family, enter into foster care or be adopted.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Infertility is the main reason parents seek to adopt children they are not related to.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] One study shows this accounted for 80% of unrelated infant adoptions and half of adoptions through foster care.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Estimates suggest that 11–24% of Americans who cannot conceive or carry to term attempt to build a family through adoption, and that the overall rate of never-married American women who adopt is about 1.4%.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Other reasons people adopt are numerous although not well documented.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Although there are a range of reasons, the most recent study of experiences of women who adopt suggests they are most likely to be 40–44 years of age, to be currently married, to have impaired fertility, and to be childless.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Although adoption is often described as forming a "forever" family, the relationship can be ended at any time.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] The legal termination of an adoption is called disruption.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] In U.S. terminology, adoptions are *disrupted* if they are ended before being finalized, and they are *dissolved* if the relationship is ended afterwards.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] It may also be called a *failed adoption*.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] After legal finalization, the disruption process is usually initiated by adoptive parents via a court petition and is analogous to divorce proceedings.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] It is a legal avenue unique to adoptive parents as disruption/dissolution does not apply to biological kin, although biological family members are sometimes disowned or abandoned.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] The wide range of values reflects the paucity of information on the subject and demographic factors such as age; it is known that teenagers are more prone to having their adoptions disrupted than young children.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Joint adoption by same-sex couples is legal in 34 countries as of March 2022, and additionally in various sub-national territories.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Adoption may also be in the form of stepchild adoption (6 additional countries), wherein one partner in a same-sex couple adopts the child of the other.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Most countries that have same-sex marriage allow joint adoption by those couples, the exceptions being Ecuador (no adoption by same-sex couples), Taiwan (stepchild adoption only) and Mexico (in one third of states with same-sex marriage).
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] A few countries with civil unions or lesser marriage rights nonetheless allow step- or joint adoption.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] In 2019, the American Community Survey (ACS) enhanced its approach to measuring same-sex couple households, explicitly distinguishing between same-sex and opposite-sex spouses or partners.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Same-sex parents, according to the ACS in 2022, were predominantly female.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Notably, 26.8% of female same-sex couple households had children under 18, in contrast to 8.2% of male same-sex couple households.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] In homes with children, female same-sex couples were almost 12% more likely to have biological children compared with male same-sex couples; however, male same-sex couples were 18.5% more likely to adopt and were less likely to have stepchildren.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] The biological relationship between a parent and child is important, and the separation of the two has led to concerns about adoption.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] This theory is supported in another more qualitative study wherein adoptive relationships marked by sameness in likes, personality, and appearance, were associated with both adult adoptees and adoptive parents reporting being happier with the adoption.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Other studies provide evidence that adoptive relationships can form along other lines.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Noting that adoptees seemed to be more likely to experience problems such as drug addiction, the study speculated that adoptive parents might invest more in adoptees not because they favor them, but because they are more likely than genetic children to need the help.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Psychologists' findings regarding the importance of early mother-infant bonding created some concern about whether parents who adopt older infants or toddlers after birth have missed some crucial period for the child's development.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Beyond the foundational issues, the unique questions posed for adoptive parents are varied.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] They include how to respond to stereotypes, answering questions about heritage, and how best to maintain connections with biological kin when in an open adoption.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] One author suggests a common question adoptive parents have is: "Will we love the child even though he/she is not our biological child?" A specific concern for many parents is accommodating an adoptee in the classroom.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Familiar lessons like "draw your family tree" or "trace your eye color back through your parents and grandparents to see where your genes come from" could be hurtful to children who were adopted and do not know this biological information.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Numerous suggestions have been made to substitute new lessons, e.g., focusing on "family orchards".
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Adopting older children presents other parenting issues.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Some children from foster care have histories of maltreatment, such as physical and psychological neglect, physical abuse, and sexual abuse, and are at risk of developing psychiatric problems.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Such children are at risk of developing a disorganized attachment.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] (1990, 1995) found that 80% of abused and maltreated infants in their sample exhibited disorganized attachment styles.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Disorganized attachment is associated with a number of developmental problems, including dissociative symptoms, as well as depressive, anxious, and acting-out symptoms.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] "Attachment is an active process—it can be secure or insecure, maladaptive or productive." In the U.K., some adoptions fail because the adoptive parents do not get sufficient support to deal with difficult, traumatized children.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] This is a false economy as local authority care for these children is extremely expensive.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Similar mechanisms appear to be at work in the physical development of adoptees.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Danish and American researchers conducting studies on the genetic contribution to body mass index found correlations between an adoptee's weight class and his biological parents' BMI while finding no relationship with the adoptive family environment.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Moreover, about one-half of inter-individual differences were due to individual non-shared influences.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] These differences in development appear to play out in the way young adoptees deal with major life events.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] In the case of parental divorce, adoptees have been found to respond differently from children who have not been adopted.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Recent research has shown that adoptive parenting may have impacts on adoptive children, it has been shown that warm adoptive parenting reduces internalizing and externalizing problems of the adoptive children over time.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Another study shows that warm adoptive parenting at 27 months predicted lower levels of child externalizing problems at ages 6 and 7.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Several factors affect the decision to release or raise the child.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] White adolescents tend to give up their babies to non-relatives, whereas black adolescents are more likely to receive support from their own community in raising the child and also in the form of informal adoption by relatives.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Studies by Leynes and by Festinger and Young, Berkman, and Rehr found that, for pregnant adolescents, the decision to release the child for adoption depended on the attitude toward adoption held by the adolescent's mother.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Another study found that pregnant adolescents whose mothers had a higher level of education were more likely to release their babies for adoption.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Research suggests that women who choose to release their babies for adoption are more likely to be younger, enrolled in school, and have lived in a two-parent household at age 10, than those who kept and raised their babies.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] There is limited research on the consequences of adoption for the original parents, and the findings have been mixed.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] One study found that those who released their babies for adoption were less comfortable with their decision than those who kept their babies.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] However, levels of comfort over both groups were high, and those who released their child were similar to those who kept their child in ratings of life satisfaction, relationship satisfaction, and positive future outlook for schooling, employment, finances, and marriage.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Subsequent research found that adolescent mothers who chose to release their babies for adoption were more likely to experience feelings of sorrow and regret over their decision than those who kept their babies.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] However, these feelings decreased significantly from one year after birth to the end of the second year.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] More recent research found that in a sample of mothers who had released their children for adoption four to 12 years prior, every participant had frequent thoughts of their lost child.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] For most, thoughts were both negative and positive in that they produced both feelings of sadness and joy.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Those who experienced the greatest portion of positive thoughts were those who had open, rather than closed or time-limited mediated, adoptions.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] In another study that compared mothers who released their children to those who raised them, mothers who released their children were more likely to delay their next pregnancy, to delay marriage, and to complete job training.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] However, both groups reached lower levels of education than their peers who were never pregnant.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Another study found similar consequences for choosing to release a child for adoption.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Adolescent mothers who released their children were more likely to reach a higher level of education and to be employed than those who kept their children.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] They also waited longer before having their next child.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Most of the research that exists on adoption effects on the birth parents was conducted with samples of adolescents, or with women who were adolescents when carrying their babies—little data exists for birth parents from other populations.
[src:ritual/adoption-p01] Furthermore, there is a lack of longitudinal data that may elucidate long-term social and psychological consequences for birth parents who choose to place their children for adoption.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Previous research on adoption has led to assumptions that indicate that there is a heightened risk in terms of psychological development and social relationships for adoptees.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Yet, such assumptions have been clarified as flawed due to methodological failures.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] But more recent studies have been supportive in indicating more accurate information and results about the similarities, differences and overall lifestyles of adoptees.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Adoptees are four times more likely to attempt suicide than other people.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Evidence about the development of adoptees can be supported in newer studies.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] It can be said that adoptees, in some respect, tend to develop differently from the general population.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] This can be seen in many aspects of life, but usually can be found as a greater risk around the time of adolescence.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] For example, it has been found that many adoptees experience difficulty in establishing a sense of identity.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] There are many ways in which the concept of identity can be defined.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] It is true in all cases that identity construction is an ongoing process of development, change and maintenance of identifying with the self.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Research has shown that adolescence is a time of identity progression rather than regression.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] One's identity tends to lack stability in the beginning years of life but gains a more stable sense in later periods of childhood and adolescence.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Typically associated with a time of experimentation, there are endless factors that go into the construction of one's identity.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] As well as being many factors, there are many types of identities one can associate with.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Some categories of identity include gender, sexuality, class, racial and religious, etc.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] For transracial and international adoptees, tension is generally found in the categories of racial, ethnic and national identification.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Because of this, the strength and functionality of family relationships play a huge role in its development and outcome of identity construction.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Transracial and transnational adoptees tend to develop feelings of a lack of acceptance because of such racial, ethnic, and cultural differences.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Therefore, exposing transracial and transnational adoptees to their "cultures of origin" is important in order to better develop a sense of identity and appreciation for cultural diversity.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Identity construction and reconstruction for transnational adoptees the instant they are adopted.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] For example, based upon specific laws and regulations of the United States, the Child Citizen Act of 2000 makes sure to grant immediate U.S. citizenship to adoptees.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Identity is defined both by what one is and what one is not.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Adoptees born into one family lose an identity and then borrow one from the adopting family.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] The formation of identity is a complicated process and there are many factors that affect its outcome.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] From a perspective of looking at issues in adoption circumstances, the people involved and affected by adoption (the biological parent, the adoptive parent and the adoptee) can be known as the "triad members and state".
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Adoption may threaten triad members' sense of identity.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Triad members often express feelings related to confused identity and identity crises because of differences between the triad relationships.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Adoption, for some, precludes a complete or integrated sense of self.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Triad members may experience themselves as incomplete, deficient, or unfinished.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] They state that they lack feelings of well-being, integration, or solidity associated with a fully developed identity.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Family plays a vital role in identity formation.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] This is not only true in childhood but also in adolescence.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Identity (gender/sexual/ethnic/religious/family) is still forming during adolescence and family holds a vital key to this.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] The research seems to be unanimous; a stable, secure, loving, honest and supportive family in which all members feel safe to explore their identity is necessary for the formation of a sound identity.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Transracial and International adoptions are some factors that play a significant role in the identity construction of adoptees.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Many tensions arise from relationships built between the adoptee(s) and their family.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] These include being "different" from the parent(s), developing a positive racial identity, and dealing with racial/ethnic discrimination.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] These tensions also tend to create questions for the adoptee, as well as the family, to contemplate.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Some common questions include what will happen if the family is more naïve to the ways of socially constructed life?
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Will tensions arise if this is the case?
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] What if the very people that are supposed to be modeling a sound identity are in fact riddled with insecurities?
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Ginni Snodgrass answers these questions in the following way.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] The secrecy in an adoptive family and the denial that the adoptive family is different builds dysfunction into it.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] "... social workers and insecure adoptive parents have structured a family relationship that is based on dishonesty, evasions and exploitation.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] To believe that good relationships will develop on such a foundation is psychologically unsound" (Lawrence).
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Secrecy erects barriers to forming a healthy identity.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] The research says that the dysfunction, untruths and evasiveness that can be present in adoptive families not only makes identity formation impossible, but also directly works against it.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] What effect on identity formation is present if the adoptee knows they are adopted but has no information about their biological parents?
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Adolescent adoptees are overrepresented among those who join sub-cultures, run away, become pregnant, or totally reject their families.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] The adoptee population does, however, seem to be more at risk for certain behavioral issues.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Researchers from the University of Minnesota studied adolescents who had been adopted and found that adoptees were twice as likely as non-adopted people to develop oppositional defiant disorder (ODD) and attention deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD), with an 8% rate in the general population.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Suicide risks were also significantly greater than the general population.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Swedish researchers found both international and domestic adoptees undertook suicide at much higher rates than non-adopted peers; with international adoptees and female international adoptees, in particular, at highest risk.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Nevertheless, work on adult adoptees has found that the additional risks faced by adoptees are largely confined to adolescence.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Young adult adoptees were shown to be alike with adults from biological families and scored better than adults raised in alternative family types including single parent and step-families.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Moreover, while adult adoptees showed more variability than their non-adopted peers on a range of psychosocial measures, adult adoptees exhibited more similarities than differences with adults who had not been adopted.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] There have been many cases of remediation or the reversibility of early trauma.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] For example, in one of the earliest studies conducted, Professor Goldfarb in England concluded that some children adjust well socially and emotionally despite their negative experiences of institutional deprivation in early childhood.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Other researchers also found that prolonged institutionalization does not necessarily lead to emotional problems or character defects in all children.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] This suggests that there will always be some children who fare well, who are resilient, regardless of their experiences in early childhood.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Furthermore, much of the research on psychological outcomes for adoptees draws from clinical populations.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] This suggests that conclusions such that adoptees are more likely to have behavioral problems such as ODD and ADHD may be biased.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Since the proportion of adoptees that seek mental health treatment is small, psychological outcomes for adoptees compared to those for the general population are more similar than some researchers propose.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] While adoption studies have shown that by adulthood the personalities of adopted siblings are little or no more similar than random pairs of strangers, the parenting style of adoptive parents may still play a role in the outcome of their adoptive children.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Research has suggested that adoptive parents can have impacts on adoptees as well, several recent studies have shown that warm adoptive parenting can reduce behavioral problems of adopted children over time.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Adopted children are more likely to experience psychological and behavioral problems than non-adopted peers.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Children who were older than four at the time of their adoption experience more psychological problems than those who were younger.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] According to study in the UK, adopted children can have mental health problems that do not improve even four years after their adoption.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Children with multiple adverse childhood experiences are more likely to have mental health problems.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] The study suggests that to identify and treat mental health problems early, care professionals and the adopting parents need detailed biographical information about the child's life.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Another study in the UK suggests that adopted children are more likely to suffer from post-traumatic stress (PTS) than the general population.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Their PTS symptoms depend on the type of adverse experiences they went through and knowledge of their history offers an option for tailored support.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] There is evidence that shows the adoptees of LGBT families and those in heterosexual families have no significant differences in development.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] One of the main arguments used against same-sex adoption is that a child needs a mother and a father in the home to develop properly.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Along with this, a 2009 study showed again that sexual orientation of parents does not affect externalizing and internalized problems, but family functioning and income can affect adjustment, especially for older adoptees.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] "Late-discovery adoption" is a term used to describe the situation where an adopted individual first discovers that they are adopted at a later age than is universally considered to be appropriate, often well into adulthood.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Adopted individuals who discover their adoption status at a later age are referred to as late-discovery adoptees (LDAs).
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Failure of the adoptive parent(s) to disclose adoption status to a child is an outdated adoption practice that was once fairly common for adoptees born in the 1930s, 1940s and 1950s.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Since the 1970s, it has been socially unacceptable to keep the truth from adopted individuals regarding their genetic origins.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] In Western culture, many see the common image of a family as being that of a heterosexual couple with biological children.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] This idea places alternative family forms outside the norm.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] As a consequence – research indicates – disparaging views of adoptive families exist, along with doubts concerning the strength of their family bonds.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] The most recent adoption attitudes survey completed by the Evan Donaldson Institute provides further evidence of this stigma.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Nearly one-third of the surveyed population believed adoptees are less-well adjusted, more prone to medical issues, and predisposed to drug and alcohol problems.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Additionally, 40–45% thought adoptees were more likely to have behavior problems and trouble at school.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] In contrast, the same study indicated adoptive parents were viewed favorably, with nearly 90% describing them as "lucky, advantaged, and unselfish".
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] The majority of people state that their primary source of information about adoption comes from friends and family and the news media.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Nevertheless, most people report the media provides them a favorable view of adoption; 72% indicated receiving positive impressions.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] There is, however, still substantial criticism of the media's adoption coverage.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Some adoption blogs, for example, criticized *Meet the Robinsons* for using outdated orphanage imagery as did advocacy non-profit The Evan B.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] The stigmas associated with adoption are amplified for children in foster care.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Negative perceptions result in the belief that such children are so troubled it would be impossible to adopt them and create "normal" families.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Attitude toward Adoption Questionnaire (ATAQ): this questionnaire was first developed by Abdollahzadeh, Chaloyi and Mahmoudi (2019).
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Preliminary Edition: This questionnaire has 23 items based on the Likert scale of 1 (totally Disagree), up to 5 (Totally Agree) being obtained after refining the items designed to construct the present tool and per-study study.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] The analysis of item and initial psychometric analyses indicate that there are two factors in it.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] The results of exploratory factor analysis by main components with varimax rotation indicated two components of attitude toward adoption being named respectively cognitive as the aspects of attitude toward adoption and behavioral-emotional aspects of attitude toward adoption.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] These two components explained 43.25% of the variance of the total sample.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Cronbach's alpha coefficient was used to measure the reliability of the questionnaire.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Cronbach's alpha coefficient was 0.709 for the whole questionnaire, 0.71 for the first component, and 0.713 for the second one.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] In addition, there was a significant positive relationship between desired social tendencies and the cognitive aspect of attitude toward adoption as well as the behavioral -emotional aspects of attitude toward adoption (P ≤ 0.01).
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Family preservation is the emphasis that, if possible, mothers and children should be kept together.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] In the U.S., this was clearly illustrated by the shift in policy of the New York Foundling Home, an adoption-institution that is among the country's oldest and one that had pioneered sealed records.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] It established three new principles including "to prevent placements of children...", reflecting the belief that children would be better served by staying with their biological families, a striking shift in policy that remains in force today.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] In addition, groups such as Origins USA (founded in 1997) started to actively speak about family preservation and the rights of mothers.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] The intellectual tone of these reform movements was influenced by the publishing of *The Primal Wound* by Nancy Verrier.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] "Primal wound" is described as the "devastation which the infant feels because of separation from its birth mother.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Forced adoption has also been enforced with the rationale of child welfare.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] The children of unwed or single mothers are commonly the target of such forced adoption.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] This was prominent during baby scoop era in the 1950s through the 1970s in the anglosphere.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] The children of parents in poverty have also been targeted for forced adoption under the rationale of child welfare.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] This was often the case for Verdingkinder or "contract children" in Switzerland between the 1850s through the middle of the twentieth century.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Removing children of ethnic minorities from their families to be adopted by those of the dominant ethnic group has been used as a method of forced assimilation.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Forced adoption based on ethnicity occurred during World War II.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] In German-occupied Poland, it is estimated that 200,000 Polish children with purportedly Aryan traits were removed from their families and given to German or Austrian couples, and only 25,000 returned to their families after the war.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] The Stolen Generation of Aboriginal people in Australia were affected by similar policies, as were Native Americans in the United States and First Nations of Canada.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] These practices have become significant social and political issues in recent years, and in many cases the policies have changed.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] The United States, for example, now has the 1978 Indian Child Welfare Act, which allows the tribe and family of a Native American child to be involved in adoption decisions, with preference being given to adoption within the child's tribe.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] While forced assimilation usually revolves around ethnicity, assimilating children of political minorities has also occurred.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] In Spain under Francisco Franco's 1939–1975 dictatorship the newborns of some left-wing opponents of the regime, or unmarried or poor couples, were removed from their mothers and adopted.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] New mothers were frequently told their babies had died suddenly after birth and the hospital had taken care of their burials, when in fact they were given or sold to another family.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] It is believed that up to 300,000 babies were involved.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] These practices—which allegedly involved doctors, nurses, nuns and priests—outlived Franco's death in 1975 and carried on as an illegal baby trafficking network until 1987 when a new law regulating adoption was introduced.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Adoption is usually managed by judges, bureaucrats and social workers.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Profiting from giving or receiving orphans has incentivized abusive practices.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Baby farming is the practice of accepting custody of a child in return for payment.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] This was most common in Victorian Britain.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Illegitimacy and its attendant social stigma were usually the impetus for a mother's decision to give her child to a baby farmer.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Baby 'farmers' would sometimes neglect or murder the babies to keep costs down.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Child harvesting is the practice of rearing human children to be sold, typically for adoption.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Poor mothers have used street clinics, known as "baby factories", to deliver babies to be adopted by richer women for payment.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] While this can be voluntary, baby factories have also coerced or abducted women into such facilities to be raped in order to sell their babies for adoption.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Organized rings in Nairobi are known to abduct the children of homeless mothers sleeping on the street.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] During the One Child Policy in China, when women were only allowed to have one child, local governments would often allow the woman to give birth and then they would take the baby away.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Child traffickers, often paid by the government, would sell the children to orphanages that would arrange international adoptions worth tens of thousands of dollars, turning a profit for the government.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Adoption practices have changed significantly over the course of the 20th century, with each new movement labeled, in some way, as reform.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Beginning in the 1970s, efforts to improve adoption became associated with opening records and encouraging family preservation.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] These ideas arose from suggestions that the secrecy inherent in modern adoption may influence the process of forming an identity, create confusion regarding genealogy, and provide little in the way of medical history.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Adopted people have long sought to undo these laws so that they can obtain their own original birth certificates.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Movements to unseal original birth certificates and other adoption records for adopted people proliferated in the 1970s along with increased acceptance of illegitimacy.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] In the United States, Jean Paton founded Orphan Voyage in 1954, and Florence Fisher founded the Adoptees' Liberty Movement Association (ALMA) in 1971, calling sealed records "an affront to human dignity".
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] While in 1975, Emma May Vilardi created the first mutual-consent registry, the International Soundex Reunion Registry (ISRR), allowing those separated by adoption to locate one another. and Lee Campbell and other birthmothers established CUB (Concerned United Birthparents).
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Similar ideas were taking hold globally with grass-roots organizations like Parent Finders in Canada and Jigsaw in Australia.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] In 1975, England and Wales opened records on moral grounds.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] A coalition of New York and national adoptee rights activists successfully worked to overturn a restrictive 83-year-old law in 2019, and adult adopted people born in New York, as well as their descendants, today have the right to request and obtain their own original birth certificates.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] In 2024, Minnesota became the fifteenth state to ensure adopted people have the legal right to obtain their original birth certificate.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] In 2025, Georgia enacted a law that restored the right to adult adopted people to request their own original birth records, becoming the sixteenth state in the United States to do so.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Since the 1970s, changes in social attitudes have resulted in examination of the language used in adoption and shifts in language use.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Controversies in adoption reform efforts have been reflected in the varying terminology recommended by adoptive parents, birth parents, adoptees, and professionals involved in the adoption process such as social workers.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Two of the contrasting sets of terms are commonly referred to as "positive adoption language" (PAL, sometimes called "respectful adoption language" or RAL), and "honest adoption language".
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] As adoption search and support organizations developed, there were challenges to the language in common use at the time.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] In contrast, proponents of "honest adoption language" (HAL) emphasize the value of the family relationships that existed prior to legal adoption and note that mothers who have "voluntarily surrendered" children seldom view it as a choice that was freely made.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Proponents of "honest language adoption" argue that the use of the term "birth mother" dehumanizes women who have given birth, likening them to an incubator, and does not reflect that mother-child relationships continue after the physical act of giving birth.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Estimates for the extent of search behavior by adoptees have proven elusive; studies show significant variation.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] In part, the problem stems from the small adoptee population which makes random surveying difficult, if not impossible.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Nevertheless, some indication of the level of search interest by adoptees can be gleaned from the case of England and Wales which opened adoptees' birth records in 1975.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Office for National Statistics has projected that 33% of all adoptees would eventually request a copy of their original birth records, exceeding original forecasts made in 1975 when it was believed that only a small fraction of the adoptee population would request their records.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] The projection is known to underestimate the true search rate, however, since many adoptees of the era get their birth records by other means.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] It is speculated by adoption researchers, however, that the reasons given are incomplete: although such information could be communicated by a third-party, interviews with adoptees, who sought reunion, found they expressed a need to actually meet biological relations.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] It appears the desire for reunion is linked to the adoptee's interaction with and acceptance within the community.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Internally focused theories suggest some adoptees possess ambiguities in their sense of self, impairing their ability to present a consistent identity.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Reunion helps resolve the lack of self-knowledge.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Externally focused theories, in contrast, suggest that reunion is a way for adoptees to overcome social stigma.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] The externally focused rationale for reunion suggests adoptees may be well adjusted and happy within their adoptive families, but will search as an attempt to resolve experiences of social stigma.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Some adoptees reject the idea of reunion.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] It is unclear, though, what differentiates adoptees who search from those who do not.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] In sum, reunions can bring a variety of issues for adoptees and parents.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Nevertheless, most reunion results appear to be positive.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] In the largest study to date (based on the responses of 1,007 adoptees and relinquishing parents), 90% responded that reunion was a beneficial experience.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] This does not, however, imply ongoing relationships were formed between adoptee and parent nor that this was the goal.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Attitudes and laws regarding adoption vary greatly.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Whereas all cultures make arrangements whereby children whose birth parents are unavailable to rear them can be brought up by others, not all cultures have the concept of adoption, that is treating unrelated children as equivalent to biological children of the adoptive parents.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] Under Islamic Law, for example, adopted children must keep their original surname to be identified with blood relations, and, traditionally, women wear a hijab in the presence of males in their adoptive households.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] In Egypt, these cultural distinctions have led to making adoption illegal opting instead for a system of foster care.
[src:ritual/adoption-p02] In some countries, such as the United States, "Homecoming Day" is the day when an adoptee is officially united with their new adoptive family.
[src:ritual/ritual] A **ritual** is a repeated, structured sequence of actions or behaviors that alters the internal or external state of an individual, group, or environment, regardless of conscious understanding, emotional context, or symbolic meaning.
[src:ritual/ritual] Traditionally associated with gestures, words, or revered objects, rituals also occur in non-human species, such as elephant mourning or corvid object-leaving.
[src:ritual/ritual] They may be prescribed by tradition, including religious practices, and are often characterized by formalism, traditionalism, rule-governance, and performance.
[src:ritual/ritual] Rituals are a feature of all known human societies.
[src:ritual/ritual] They include not only the worship rites and sacraments of organized religions and cults, but also rites of passage, atonement and purification rites, oaths of allegiance, dedication ceremonies, coronations and presidential inaugurations, marriages, funerals and more.
[src:ritual/ritual] Even common actions like hand-shaking and saying "hello" may be termed as *rituals*.
[src:ritual/ritual] The field of ritual studies has seen a number of conflicting definitions of the term.
[src:ritual/ritual] One given by Kyriakidis is that a ritual is an outsider's or "etic" category for a set activity (or set of actions) that, to the outsider, seems irrational, non-contiguous, or illogical.
[src:ritual/ritual] The term can be used also by the insider or "emic" performer as an acknowledgement that this activity can be seen as such by the uninitiated onlooker.
[src:ritual/ritual] In psychology, the term *ritual* is sometimes used in a technical sense for a repetitive behavior systematically used by a person to neutralize or prevent anxiety; it can be a symptom of obsessive–compulsive disorder but obsessive-compulsive ritualistic behaviors are generally isolated activities.
[src:ritual/ritual] The English word *ritual* derives from the Latin *ritualis,* "that which pertains to rite *(ritus*)".
[src:ritual/ritual] In Roman juridical and religious usage, *ritus* was the proven way *(mos)* of doing something, or "correct performance, custom".
[src:ritual/ritual] The original concept of *ritus* may be related to the Sanskrit *ṛtá* ("visible order)" in Vedic religion, "the lawful and regular order of the normal, and therefore proper, natural and true structure of cosmic, worldly, human and ritual events".
[src:ritual/ritual] The word "ritual" is first recorded in English in 1570, and came into use in the 1600s to mean "the prescribed order of performing religious services" or more particularly a book of these prescriptions.
[src:ritual/ritual] There are hardly any limits to the kind of actions that may be incorporated into a ritual.
[src:ritual/ritual] The rites of past and present societies have typically involved special gestures and words, recitation of fixed texts, performance of special music, songs or dances, processions, manipulation of certain objects, use of special dresses, consumption of special food, drink, or drugs, and much more.
[src:ritual/ritual] Catherine Bell argues that rituals can be characterized by formalism, traditionalism, invariance, rule-governance, sacral symbolism and performance.
[src:ritual/ritual] Ritual uses a limited and rigidly organized set of expressions which anthropologists call a "restricted code" (in opposition to a more open "elaborated code").
[src:ritual/ritual] Maurice Bloch argues that ritual obliges participants to use this formal oratorical style, which is limited in intonation, syntax, vocabulary, loudness, and fixity of order.
[src:ritual/ritual] In adopting this style, ritual leaders' speech becomes more style than content.
[src:ritual/ritual] Because this formal speech limits what can be said, it induces "acceptance, compliance, or at least forbearance with regard to any overt challenge".
[src:ritual/ritual] Bloch argues that this form of ritual communication makes rebellion impossible and revolution the only feasible alternative.
[src:ritual/ritual] Ritual tends to support traditional forms of social hierarchy and authority, and maintains the assumptions on which the authority is based from challenge.
[src:ritual/ritual] Rituals appeal to tradition and are generally continued to repeat historical precedent, religious rite, mores, or ceremony accurately.
[src:ritual/ritual] Traditionalism varies from formalism in that the ritual may not be formal yet still makes an appeal to the historical trend.
[src:ritual/ritual] An example is the American Thanksgiving dinner, which may not be formal, yet is ostensibly based on an event from the early Puritan settlement of America.
[src:ritual/ritual] Thus, the appeal to history is important rather than accurate historical transmission.
[src:ritual/ritual] Catherine Bell states that ritual is also invariant, implying careful choreography.
[src:ritual/ritual] This is less an appeal to traditionalism than a striving for timeless repetition.
[src:ritual/ritual] The key to invariance is bodily discipline, as in monastic prayer and meditation meant to mold dispositions and moods.
[src:ritual/ritual] This bodily discipline is frequently performed in unison, by groups.
[src:ritual/ritual] Rituals tend to be governed by rules, a feature somewhat like formalism.
[src:ritual/ritual] Rules impose norms on the chaos of behavior, either defining the outer limits of what is acceptable or choreographing each move.
[src:ritual/ritual] Individuals are held to communally approved customs that evoke a legitimate communal authority that can constrain the possible outcomes.
[src:ritual/ritual] Historically, war in most societies has been bound by highly ritualized constraints that limit the legitimate means by which war was waged.
[src:ritual/ritual] Activities appealing to supernatural beings are easily considered rituals, although the appeal may be quite indirect, expressing only a generalized belief in the existence of the sacred demanding a human response.
[src:ritual/ritual] National flags, for example, may be considered more than signs representing a country.
[src:ritual/ritual] The flag stands for larger symbols such as freedom, democracy, free enterprise or national superiority.
[src:ritual/ritual] Particular objects become sacral symbols through a process of consecration which effectively creates the sacred by setting it apart from the profane.
[src:ritual/ritual] Boy Scouts and the armed forces in any country teach the official ways of folding, saluting and raising the flag, thus emphasizing that the flag should never be treated as just a piece of cloth.
[src:ritual/ritual] The performance of ritual creates a theatrical-like frame around the activities, symbols and events that shape participant's experience and cognitive ordering of the world, simplifying the chaos of life and imposing a more or less coherent system of categories of meaning onto it.
[src:ritual/ritual] The theatricality of ritual may overlap with performance art.
[src:ritual/ritual] However, rituals can fall in more than one category or genre, and may be grouped in a variety of other ways.
[src:ritual/ritual] A rite of passage is a ritual event that marks a person's transition from one status to another, including adoption, baptism, coming of age, graduation, inauguration, engagement, and marriage.
[src:ritual/ritual] Rites of passage may also include initiation into groups not tied to a formal stage of life such as a fraternity.
[src:ritual/ritual] Wherein the initiates are separated from their old identities through physical and symbolic means.
[src:ritual/ritual] Wherein the initiated are "betwixt and between".
[src:ritual/ritual] , a condition of ambiguity or disorientation in which initiates have been stripped of their old identities, but have not yet acquired their new one.
[src:ritual/ritual] ("threshold people") are necessarily ambiguous".
[src:ritual/ritual] or emotional bond of community between them.
[src:ritual/ritual] This stage may be marked by ritual ordeals or ritual training.
[src:ritual/ritual] Wherein the initiates are symbolically confirmed in their new identity and community.
[src:ritual/ritual] Anthropologist Victor Turner defines rites of affliction actions that seek to mitigate spirits or supernatural forces that inflict humans with bad luck, illness, gynecological troubles, physical injuries, and other such misfortunes.
[src:ritual/ritual] These rites may include forms of spirit divination (consulting oracles) to establish causes—and rituals that heal, purify, exorcise, and protect.
[src:ritual/ritual] The misfortune experienced may include individual health, but also broader climate-related issues such as drought or plagues of insects.
[src:ritual/ritual] Healing rites performed by shamans frequently identify social disorder as the cause, and make the restoration of social relationships the cure.
[src:ritual/ritual] Turner uses the example of the Isoma ritual among the Ndembu of northwestern Zambia to illustrate.
[src:ritual/ritual] The Isoma rite of affliction is used to cure a childless woman of infertility.
[src:ritual/ritual] Infertility is the result of a "structural tension between matrilineal descent and virilocal marriage" (i.e., the tension a woman feels between her mother's family, to whom she owes allegiance, and her husband's family among whom she must live).
[src:ritual/ritual] Shamanic and other ritual may effect a psychotherapeutic cure, leading anthropologists such as Jane Atkinson to theorize how.
[src:ritual/ritual] Atkinson argues that the effectiveness of a shamanic ritual for an individual may depend upon a wider audiences acknowledging the shaman's power, which may lead to the shaman placing greater emphasis on engaging the audience than in the healing of the patient.
[src:ritual/ritual] Many cultures have rites associated with death and mourning, such as the last rites and wake in Christianity, *shemira* in Judaism, the *antyesti* in Hinduism, and the *antam sanskar* in Sikhism.
[src:ritual/ritual] These rituals often provide a structured way for communities to grieve and honor the deceased.
[src:ritual/ritual] In Tibetan Buddhism, for example, the rituals described in the *Bardo Thodol* guide the soul through the stages of death, aiming for spiritual liberation or enlightenment.
[src:ritual/ritual] In Islam, the Janazah prayer is an communal act of grief.
[src:ritual/ritual] Indigenous practices, such as the Australian Aboriginal smoking ceremony, intended to cleanse the spirit of the departed and ensure a safe journey to the afterlife.
[src:ritual/ritual] In many traditions can be found the belief that when man was first made the creator bestowed soul upon him, while the earth provided the body.
[src:ritual/ritual] In Genesis is offered the following description of the creation of man: "And the Lord God formed man of the dust of the ground, and breathed into his nostrils the breath of life; and man became a living soul".
[src:ritual/ritual] As a result at the moment of death each of the two elements needs to be returned to its source, the body returns to earth, while the soul to the heavenly creator, by means of the funerary ritual.
[src:ritual/ritual] Calendrical and commemorative rites are ritual events marking particular times of year, or a fixed period since an important event.
[src:ritual/ritual] Calendrical rituals give social meaning to the passage of time, creating repetitive weekly, monthly or yearly cycles.
[src:ritual/ritual] Some rites are oriented towards a culturally defined moment of change in the climatic cycle, such as solar terms or the changing of seasons, or they may mark the inauguration of an activity such as planting, harvesting, or moving from winter to summer pasture during the agricultural cycle.
[src:ritual/ritual] Calendrical rites impose a cultural order on nature.
[src:ritual/ritual] This genre of ritual encompasses forms of sacrifice and offering meant to praise, please or placate divine powers.
[src:ritual/ritual] According to early anthropologist Edward Tylor, such sacrifices are gifts given in hope of a return.
[src:ritual/ritual] Catherine Bell, however, points out that sacrifice covers a range of practices from those that are manipulative and "magical" to those of pure devotion.
[src:ritual/ritual] Hindu puja, for example, appear to have no other purpose than to please the deity.
[src:ritual/ritual] According to Marcel Mauss, sacrifice is distinguished from other forms of offering by being consecrated, and hence sanctified.
[src:ritual/ritual] As a consequence, the offering is usually destroyed in the ritual to transfer it to the deities.
[src:ritual/ritual] Rites of feasting and fasting are those through which a community publicly expresses an adherence to basic, shared religious values, rather than to the overt presence of deities as is found in rites of affliction where feasting or fasting may also take place.
[src:ritual/ritual] It encompasses a range of performances such as communal fasting during Ramadan by Muslims; the slaughter of pigs in New Guinea; Carnival festivities; or penitential processions in Catholicism.
[src:ritual/ritual] Victor Turner described this "cultural performance" of basic values a "social drama".
[src:ritual/ritual] Such dramas allow the social stresses that are inherent in a particular culture to be expressed and worked out symbolically in a ritual catharsis; as the social tensions continue to persist outside the ritual, pressure mounts for the ritual's cyclical performance.
[src:ritual/ritual] In Carnival, for example, the practice of masking allows people to be what they are not, and acts as a general social leveller, erasing otherwise tense social hierarchies in a festival that emphasizes play outside the bounds of normal social limits.
[src:ritual/ritual] Yet outside carnival, social tensions of race, class and gender persist, hence requiring the repeated periodic release found in the festival.
[src:ritual/ritual] A water rite is a rite or ceremonial custom that uses water as its central feature.
[src:ritual/ritual] Typically, a person is immersed or bathed as a symbol of religious indoctrination or ritual purification.
[src:ritual/ritual] Rites that use water are not considered water rites if it is not their central feature.
[src:ritual/ritual] For example, having water to drink during or after ritual is common, but does not make that ritual a water ritual unless the drinking of water is a central activity such as in the Church of All Worlds waterkin rite.
[src:ritual/ritual] Fertility rites are religious rituals that are intended to stimulate reproduction in humans or in the natural world.
[src:ritual/ritual] A group of people performing such rites is a fertility cult.
[src:ritual/ritual] Such rites may involve the sacrifice of "a primal animal, which must be sacrificed in the cause of fertility or even creation".
[src:ritual/ritual] Sexual rituals fall into two categories: culture-created, and natural behaviour, the human animal having developed sex rituals from evolutionary instincts for reproduction, which are then integrated into society, and elaborated to include aspects such as marriage rites, dances, etc.
[src:ritual/ritual] Sometimes sexual rituals are highly formalized and/or part of religious activity, as in the cases of *hieros gamos*, the hierodule, and Ordo Templi Orientis (O.T.O.).
[src:ritual/ritual] As a "dramaturgy of power" comprehensive ritual systems may create a cosmological order that sets a ruler apart as a divine being, as in "the divine right" of European kings, or the divine Japanese Emperor.
[src:ritual/ritual] Ritual can be used as a form of resistance, as for example, in the various Cargo Cults that developed against colonial powers in the South Pacific.
[src:ritual/ritual] In such religio-political movements, Islanders would use ritual imitations of western practices (such as the building of landing strips) as a means of summoning cargo (manufactured goods) from the ancestors.
[src:ritual/ritual] Leaders of these groups characterized the present state (often imposed by colonial capitalist regimes) as a dismantling of the old social order, which they sought to restore.
[src:ritual/ritual] Rituals may also attain political significance after conflict, as is the case with the Bosnian syncretic holidays and festivals that transgress religious boundaries.
[src:ritual/ritual] Cäcilia "Cillie" Rentmeister, a German scholar of art and culture, focused her research on Rituals and Ritualizations to the question, how in ”western” and ”traditional” societies Rites of Passage are ”doing gender”, shaping and confirming womenhood and masculinity.
[src:ritual/ritual] She describes, how in the lives of women an men, ”Rites of Passage” accompany changes of status as well as all crises: pregnancy and birth, puberty and sexlife, marriage and divorce, dying and death, and also – with rites of initiation - all stages in education and profession.
[src:ritual/ritual] In this context, she also notes that ”modern” cultures are by no means ”ritually poor” in contrast to the ”ritually rich” in ”traditional” cultures.
[src:ritual/ritual] For example, in her Essay *Women’s festivals as rites of passage.
[src:ritual/ritual] Nineteenth century "armchair anthropologists" were concerned with the basic question of how religion originated in human history.
[src:ritual/ritual] In the twentieth century their conjectural histories were replaced with new concerns around the question of what these beliefs and practices did for societies, regardless of their origin.
[src:ritual/ritual] In this view, religion was a universal, and while its content might vary enormously, it served certain basic functions such as the provision of prescribed solutions to basic human psychological and social problems, as well as expressing the central values of a society.
[src:ritual/ritual] Bronislaw Malinowski used the concept of function to address questions of individual psychological needs; A.R.
[src:ritual/ritual] Radcliffe-Brown, in contrast, looked for the function (purpose) of the institution or custom in preserving or maintaining society as a whole.
[src:ritual/ritual] They thus disagreed about the relationship of anxiety to ritual.
[src:ritual/ritual] Homans sought to resolve these opposing theories by differentiating between "primary anxieties" felt by people who lack the techniques to secure results, and "secondary (or displaced) anxiety" felt by those who have not performed the rites meant to allay primary anxiety correctly.
[src:ritual/ritual] Homans argued that purification rituals may then be conducted to dispel secondary anxiety.
[src:ritual/ritual] At one extreme we have actions which are entirely profane, entirely functional, technique pure and simple; at the other we have actions which are entirely sacred, strictly aesthetic, technically non-functional.
[src:ritual/ritual] Between these two extremes we have the great majority of social actions which partake partly of the one sphere and partly of the other.
[src:ritual/ritual] The functionalist model viewed ritual as a homeostatic mechanism to regulate and stabilize social institutions by adjusting social interactions, maintaining a group ethos, and restoring harmony after disputes.
[src:ritual/ritual] Although the functionalist model was soon superseded, later "neofunctional" theorists adopted its approach by examining the ways that ritual regulated larger ecological systems.
[src:ritual/ritual] Roy Rappaport, for example, examined the way gift exchanges of pigs between tribal groups in Papua New Guinea maintained environmental balance between humans, available food (with pigs sharing the same foodstuffs as humans) and resource base.
[src:ritual/ritual] Stephen Lansing traced how the intricate calendar of Hindu Balinese rituals served to regulate the vast irrigation systems of Bali, ensuring the optimum distribution of water over the system while limiting disputes.
[src:ritual/ritual] While most Functionalists sought to link ritual to the maintenance of social order, South African functionalist anthropologist Max Gluckman coined the phrase "rituals of rebellion" to describe a type of ritual in which the accepted social order was symbolically turned on its head.
[src:ritual/ritual] Gluckman argued that the ritual was an expression of underlying social tensions (an idea taken up by Victor Turner), and that it functioned as an institutional pressure valve, relieving those tensions through these cyclical performances.
[src:ritual/ritual] The rites ultimately functioned to reinforce social order, insofar as they allowed those tensions to be expressed without leading to actual rebellion.
[src:ritual/ritual] Claude Lévi-Strauss, the French anthropologist, regarded all social and cultural organization as symbolic systems of communication shaped by the inherent structure of the human brain.
[src:ritual/ritual] He therefore argued that the symbol systems are not reflections of social structure as the Functionalists believed, but are imposed on social relations to organize them.
[src:ritual/ritual] Lévi-Strauss thus viewed myth and ritual as complementary symbol systems, one verbal, one non-verbal.
[src:ritual/ritual] Lévi-Strauss was not concerned to develop a theory of ritual (although he did produce a four-volume analysis of myth) but was influential to later scholars of ritual such as Mary Douglas and Edmund Leach.
[src:ritual/ritual] Victor Turner combined Arnold van Gennep's model of the structure of initiation rites, and Gluckman's functionalist emphasis on the ritualization of social conflict to maintain social equilibrium, with a more structural model of symbols in ritual.
[src:ritual/ritual] Running counter to this emphasis on structured symbolic oppositions within a ritual was his exploration of the liminal phase of rites of passage, a phase in which "anti-structure" appears.
[src:ritual/ritual] In this phase, opposed states such as birth and death may be encompassed by a single act, object or phrase.
[src:ritual/ritual] The dynamic nature of symbols experienced in ritual provides a compelling personal experience; ritual is a "mechanism that periodically converts the obligatory into the desirable".
[src:ritual/ritual] Mary Douglas, a British Functionalist, extended Turner's theory of ritual structure and anti-structure with her own contrasting set of terms "grid" and "group" in the book *Natural Symbols*.
[src:ritual/ritual] Drawing on Levi-Strauss' Structuralist approach, she saw ritual as symbolic communication that constrained social behaviour.
[src:ritual/ritual] Grid is a scale referring to the degree to which a symbolic system is a shared frame of reference.
[src:ritual/ritual] Group refers to the degree people are tied into a tightly knit community.
[src:ritual/ritual] When graphed on two intersecting axes, four quadrants are possible: strong group/strong grid, strong group/weak grid, weak group/weak grid, weak group/strong grid.
[src:ritual/ritual] Douglas argued that societies with strong group or strong grid were marked by more ritual activity than those weak in either group or grid.
[src:ritual/ritual] In his analysis of rites of passage, Victor Turner argued that the liminal phase – that period 'betwixt and between' – was marked by "two models of human interrelatedness, juxtaposed and alternating": structure and anti-structure (or *communitas*).
[src:ritual/ritual] These periods of symbolic inversion have been studied in a diverse range of rituals such as pilgrimages and Yom Kippur.
[src:ritual/ritual] Beginning with Max Gluckman's concept of "rituals of rebellion", Victor Turner argued that many types of ritual also served as "social dramas" through which structural social tensions could be expressed, and temporarily resolved.
[src:ritual/ritual] Drawing on Van Gennep's model of initiation rites, Turner viewed these social dramas as a dynamic process through which the community renewed itself through the ritual creation of communitas during the "liminal phase".
[src:ritual/ritual] Turner analyzed the ritual events in 4 stages: breach in relations, crisis, redressive actions, and acts of reintegration.
[src:ritual/ritual] Like Gluckman, he argued these rituals maintain social order while facilitating disordered inversions, thereby moving people to a new status, just as in an initiation rite.
[src:ritual/ritual] Clifford Geertz also expanded on the symbolic approach to ritual that began with Victor Turner.
[src:ritual/ritual] Geertz argued that religious symbol systems provided both a "model of" reality (showing how to interpret the world as is) as well as a "model for" reality (clarifying its ideal state).
[src:ritual/ritual] Symbolic anthropologists like Geertz analyzed rituals as language-like codes to be interpreted independently as cultural systems.
[src:ritual/ritual] Geertz rejected Functionalist arguments that ritual describes social order, arguing instead that ritual actively shapes that social order and imposes meaning on disordered experience.
[src:ritual/ritual] He also differed from Gluckman and Turner's emphasis on ritual action as a means of resolving social passion, arguing instead that it simply displayed them.
[src:ritual/ritual] Whereas Victor Turner saw in ritual the potential to release people from the binding structures of their lives into a liberating anti-structure or communitas, Maurice Bloch argued that ritual produced conformity.
[src:ritual/ritual] Maurice Bloch argued that ritual communication is unusual in that it uses a special, restricted vocabulary, a small number of permissible illustrations, and a restrictive grammar.
[src:ritual/ritual] As a result, ritual utterances become very predictable, and the speaker is made anonymous in that they have little choice in what to say.
[src:ritual/ritual] The restrictive syntax reduces the ability of the speaker to make propositional arguments, and they are left, instead, with utterances that cannot be contradicted such as "I do thee wed" in a wedding.
[src:ritual/ritual] These kinds of utterances, known as performatives, prevent speakers from making political arguments through logical argument, and are typical of what Weber called traditional authority instead.
[src:ritual/ritual] Bloch's model of ritual language denies the possibility of creativity.
[src:ritual/ritual] Thomas Csordas, in contrast, analyzes how ritual language can be used to innovate.
[src:ritual/ritual] Csordas looks at groups of rituals that share performative elements ("genres" of ritual with a shared "poetics").
[src:ritual/ritual] These rituals may fall along the spectrum of formality, with some less, others more formal and restrictive.
[src:ritual/ritual] Csordas argues that innovations may be introduced in less formalized rituals.
[src:ritual/ritual] As these innovations become more accepted and standardized, they are slowly adopted in more formal rituals.
[src:ritual/ritual] In this way, even the most formal of rituals are potential avenues for creative expression.
[src:ritual/ritual] In his historical analysis of articles on ritual and rite in the *Encyclopaedia Britannica*, Talal Asad notes that from 1771 to 1852, the brief articles on ritual define it as a "book directing the order and manner to be observed in performing divine service" (i.e., as a script).
[src:ritual/ritual] There are no articles on the subject thereafter until 1910, when a new, lengthy article appeared that redefines ritual as "...a type of routine behaviour that symbolizes or expresses something".
[src:ritual/ritual] As a symbolic activity, it is no longer confined to religion, but is distinguished from technical action.
[src:ritual/ritual] The shift in definitions from script to behavior, which is likened to a text, is matched by a semantic distinction between ritual as an *outward sign* (i.e., public symbol) and *inward meaning*.
[src:ritual/ritual] Drawing on the example of Medieval monastic life in Europe, he points out that ritual in this case refers to its original meaning of the "...book directing the order and manner to be observed in performing divine service".
[src:ritual/ritual] The point of monastic discipline was to learn skills and appropriate emotions.
[src:ritual/ritual] Ethnographic observation shows ritual can create social solidarity.
[src:ritual/ritual] Douglas Foley Went to North Town, Texas, between 1973 and 1974 to study public high school culture.
[src:ritual/ritual] He used interviews, participant observation, and unstructured chatting to study racial tension and capitalist culture in his ethnography *Learning Capitalist Culture*.
[src:ritual/ritual] Foley refers to football games and Friday Night Lights as a community ritual.
[src:ritual/ritual] This ritual united the school and created a sense of solidarity and community on a weekly basis involving pep rallies and the game itself.
[src:ritual/ritual] Foley observed judgement and segregation based on class, social status, wealth, and gender.
[src:ritual/ritual] He described Friday Night Lights as a ritual that overcomes those differences: "The other, gentler, more social side of football was, of course, the emphasis on camaraderie, loyalty, friendship between players, and pulling together".
[src:ritual/ritual] Asad's work critiqued the notion that there were universal characteristics of ritual to be found in all cases.
[src:ritual/ritual] Catherine Bell has extended this idea by shifting attention from ritual as a category, to the processes of "ritualization" by which ritual is created as a cultural form in a society.
[src:ritual/ritual] Ritualization is "a way of acting that is designed and orchestrated to distinguish and privilege what is being done in comparison to other, usually more quotidian, activities".
[src:ritual/ritual] Anthropologists have also analyzed ritual via insights from other behavioral sciences.
[src:ritual/ritual] The idea that cultural rituals share behavioral similarities with personal rituals of individuals was discussed early on by Freud.
[src:ritual/ritual] Dulaney and Fiske compared ethnographic descriptions of both rituals and non-ritual doings, such as work to behavioral descriptions from clinical descriptions of obsessive–compulsive disorder (OCD).
[src:ritual/ritual] They note that OCD behavior often consists of such behavior as constantly cleaning objects, concern or disgust with bodily waste or secretions, repetitive actions to prevent harm, heavy emphasis on number or order of actions etc.
[src:ritual/ritual] They then show that ethnographic descriptions of cultural rituals contain around 5 times more of such content than ethnographic descriptions of other activities such as "work".
[src:ritual/ritual] The authors offer tentative explanations for these findings, for example that these behavioral traits are widely needed for survival, to control risk, and cultural rituals are often performed in the context of perceived collective risk.
[src:ritual/ritual] Other anthropologists have taken these insights further, and constructed more elaborate theories based on the brain functions and physiology.
[src:ritual/ritual] Liénard and Boyer suggest that commonalities between obsessive behavior in individuals and similar behavior in collective contexts possibly share similarities due to underlying mental processes they call hazard precaution.
[src:ritual/ritual] They suggest that individuals of societies seem to pay more attention to information relevant to avoiding hazards, which in turn can explain why collective rituals displaying actions of hazard precaution are so popular and prevail for long periods in cultural transmission.
[src:ritual/ritual] According to the sociologist Mervin Verbit, ritual may be understood as one of the key components of religiosity.
[src:ritual/ritual] And ritual itself may be broken down into four dimensions; content, frequency, intensity and centrality.
[src:ritual/ritual] The content of a ritual may vary from ritual to ritual, as does the frequency of its practice, the intensity of the ritual (how much of an impact it has on the practitioner), and the centrality of the ritual (in that religious tradition).
[src:ritual/ritual] In this sense, ritual is similar to Charles Glock's "practice" dimension of religiosity.
[src:ritual/ritual] In religion, a ritual can comprise the prescribed outward forms of performing the *cultus*, or cult, of a particular observation within a religion or religious denomination.
[src:ritual/ritual] Rituals often have a close connection with reverence, thus a ritual in many cases expresses reverence for a deity or idealized state of humanity.
[src:ritual/ritual] The Sumerians used the term Me (mythology) to refer to rituals, a word that was later equated with *parṣu* in the Akkadian language by the Babylonians and Assyrians.
[src:ritual/ritual] In Mesopotamia, these rituals were considered to be the property of the gods, and only certain individuals, such as kings and religious experts, had knowledge of them.
[src:ritual/ritual] From an ancient perspective, the gods themselves could also perform rituals, or acquire them from other gods to increase their power.
[src:ritual/ritual] This is a reflection of historical power struggles on a theological and political level.
[src:ritual/ritual] In Christianity, a rite is used to refer to a sacred ceremony (such as anointing of the sick), which may or may not carry the status of a sacrament depending on the Christian denomination (in Roman Catholicism, anointing of the sick is a sacrament while in Lutheranism it is not).
[src:ritual/ritual] The word "rite" is also used to denote a liturgical tradition usually emanating from a specific center; examples include the Roman Rite, the Byzantine Rite, and the Sarum Rite.
[src:ritual/ritual] Such rites may include various sub-rites.
[src:ritual/ritual] For example, the Byzantine Rite (which is used by the Eastern Orthodox, Eastern Lutheran, and Eastern Catholic churches) has Greek, Russian, and other ethnically based variants.
[src:ritual/ritual] For daily prayers, practicing Muslims must perform a ritual recitation from the Quran in Arabic while bowing and prostrating.
[src:ritual/ritual] Quranic chapter 2 prescribes rituals such as the direction to face for prayers (qiblah); pilgrimage (Hajj), and fasting in Ramadan.
[src:ritual/ritual] Iḥrām is a state of ritual purity in preparation for pilgrimage in Islam.
[src:ritual/ritual] Hajj rituals include circumambulation around the Kaʿbah....
[src:ritual/ritual] *and show us our rites* – these rites (manāsik) are presumed the rituals of ḥajj.
[src:ritual/ritual] *Truly Ṣafā and Marwah are among the rituals of God* Saʿy is the ritual travel, partway between walking and running, seven times between the two hills.
[src:ritual/ritual] In Freemasonry, rituals are scripted words and actions which employ Masonic symbolism to illustrate the principles espoused by Freemasons.
[src:ritual/ritual] These rituals are progressively taught to entrusted members during initiation into a particular Masonic rite comprising a series of degrees conferred by a Masonic body.
[src:ritual/ritual] The degrees of Freemasonry derive from the three grades of medieval craft guilds; those of "Entered Apprentice", "Journeyman" (or "Fellowcraft"), and "Master Mason".
[src:ritual/ritual] In North America, Freemasons who have been raised to the degree of "Master Mason" have the option of joining appendant bodies that offer additional degrees to those, such as those of the Scottish Rite or the York Rite.
